<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Found Guilty in Xerox Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A former Xerox copier repairman was convicted Tuesday of
gunning down seven co-workers in Hawaii's worst mass killing. A jury found Byran
Uyesugi, 40, guilty of first-degree murder, which covers multiple killings, and
attempted murder in the second degree for shooting at an eighth co-worker and
missing. The verdict means the jury believes Uyesugi was legally sane during his
Nov. 2 shooting spree at a Xerox parts warehouse.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Change in Release of Census Data Sought
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Secretary Richard Daley will propose giving the
head of the Census Bureau the final say on when to make public sampled census
data that could drastically affect the way congressional district lines are
redrawn, Census officials said Tuesday. The authority to release the
statistically adjusted data from Census 2000 currently lies with the commerce
secretary. The announcement of the proposal will come at a news conference
Wednesday, Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said Tuesday night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Number of Refugees Grows Worldwide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Conflicts in Kosovo and East Timor and wars across
Africa sent 7 million people fleeing their homes last year, bringing to 35
million the number of people worldwide who are uprooted and in need of
protection, a leading refugee organization said Tuesday. The U.S. Committee for
Refugees said more people were living in refugee camps and makeshift housing at
the end of this decade than at the start. In 1990, 29 million people were either
refugees -- defined as people forced to flee their countries -- or internally
displaced residents who leave their homes but not their countries to escape
fighting or political instability.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Nears Vote on Education Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans batted down Democratic efforts to add funds
for schools and biomedical research to a $339.5 billion measure financing next
year's education, health and labor programs as the House moved today to the
brink of a final vote on the year's biggest spending bill. With a promised veto
by President Clinton waiting in the wings, Republicans were hoping for House
passage tomorrow of a bill so controversial that it hasn't come to that
chamber's floor since 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pope Attacker Arrives in Turkey
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy on Tuesday pardoned the Turkish gunman who tried to kill
Pope John Paul II in 1981, and he was immediately delivered to authorities in
Turkey -- taking with him the answers to the mysterious assassination attempt.
Despite the pardon, Mehmet Ali Agca must now serve time in Turkey for a killing
that took place before the attack on the pope. He arrived at Istanbul's Ataturk
International Airport early Wednesday. Police backed by armored personnel
carriers blocked off the gate where he landed, CNN-Turk reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Assad Buried in Home Village
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   QARDAHA, Syria (AP) -- After a day of frenzied mourning, solemn prayers and a
bit of politicking, Syrian President Hafez Assad was laid to rest Tuesday in the
mountains where he began his climb to power. Bashar Assad, the president's
oldest surviving son and heir apparent, was jostled at the head of the coffin as
clerics, elderly men in business suits or the traditional dark cloaks and white
headdresses of Alawite Muslims, and even soldiers pressed forward. ''His death
is a national catastrophe,'' said Hafez al-Shuraiqi, 69, a former schoolmate of
the president.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accused Teen Killer To Plead Innocent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A 13-year-old middle school student charged
with killing a favorite teacher will plead innocent at his arraignment next week
on murder charges, his lawyers said today. Nathaniel Brazill, jailed under an
indictment alleging murder with a firearm, has been charged with the wrong
crimes, lawyer Robert Udell said after the teen's first appearance in court
today. A tentative arraignment date was set for June 19.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday on profit-taking in light
trading. The Nikkei shed 152.25 points, or 0.90 percent, to 16,762.70 in the
first 30 minutes of trading. On Wall Street, the Dow average rose 57.63 points
to 10,621.84 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index gained 83.15 points
to close at 3,851.06.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Angels 5, Devil Rays 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Seth Etherton won his first major league game
and Mo Vaughn hit his first homer this month as the Anaheim Angels beat the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays 5-3 on Tuesday night. Etherton allowed two runs and five
hits over five innings in his fourth career start. He put himself in position
for the win by striking out Greg Vaughn with runners on second and third to end
the fifth inning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
