<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Returns After Cyanide Spill  </HEADLINE>
By EVA KEKES
<TEXT>
<P>
   CSONGRAD, Hungary (AP) -- For centuries, Hungary's fishermen have
pulled nets bursting with fish from the Tisza River. Five months
after a deadly cyanide killed much of the river's life, fishermen
are dumping buckets of tiny fish back into the waters hoping they
will thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can hardly wait to start to work again,'' Imre Koeroesi,
54, said. ''We haven't been able to fish since last fall, and have
used up all our reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Koeroesi and other fishermen will be allowed to
return to their trade. Fishing has been banned here since more than
130,000 cubic yards of cyanide-laced water leaked from a reservoir
at an Australian-owned gold mine in Romania in January and flowed
into the Tisza, which flows into the Danube and on to the Black
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Koeroesi and other fishermen have worked hard to reintroduce
80,000 tiny catfish. They are confident the fish will flourish and
the Tisza will again provide a livelihood for those who populate
its banks.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 60 species of fish living in the Tisza
were indigenous and are being reintroduced, said Janos Goenczy,
government commissioner overseeing catastrophe-prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a good chance that we can improve the fish stock of
the river,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has set up a task force to evaluate the
extent of damage caused by the cyanide spill and another spill of
heavy metals that followed shortly after.
</P>
<P>
   While cyanide kills instantly, it dilutes fast. Nature was
fortunate that the poisoning occurred in winter before many plants
had sprouted and that it was followed by heavy flood waters that
helped wash out the remaining poisons, said Goenczy.
</P>
<P>
   Fears remain, however, that the impact of the heavy metals may
be felt for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Different living beings reacted differently to the
poisoning,'' said Goenczy. ''In some fish species the damage was
bigger than in others, while the flora was in relative safety,
given the time of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The countries affected -- Hungary, Romania, Yugoslavia and
Ukraine -- have agreed to set up a monitoring system so they can
alert each other of another such environmental catastrophe, said
Eva Montsko, Goenczy's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian government also plans to sue the Aurul company in
Australia and Romania for damages estimated at about $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the fishermen believe in the magical healing capacity of the
Tisza, their sole source of living.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who said there'd be no life here for 20 years, shouldn't
have said that,'' said Istvan Gyovai, 50, a fisherman whose deep
tan tells of the hours he's spent on the river.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he realizes that even though nature may heal the Tisza,
it will take years to restore public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it will be harder to make the world believe that
everything -- the water, the fish -- is safe here,'' he said. ''And
everybody is welcome to spend their vacation at this beautiful
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Backs Media Leakers as Felons  </HEADLINE>
Senate panel backs making leaks of classified material a felony
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Intelligence Committee reportedly
has endorsed legislation that would make disclosing classified
information to the news media a felony punishable by up to three
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members, led by Chairman Richard Shelby, R-Ala., say
existing laws make prosecutions difficult and don't encompass all
kinds of classified materials, The Washington Post reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To prosecute leakers under current law, prosecutors must show
they leaked on behalf of a foreign power or divulged ''national
defense'' data, which excludes much important information,
committee members say.
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment groups and Attorney General Janet Reno have
opposed the bill, saying criminal prosecutions are not necessarily
the best way to stop leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, along with FBI Director Louis J. Freeh and CIA Director
George J. Tenet, is scheduled to testify Wednesday at a closed
hearing of the Senate committee concerning the bill. The Post,
quoting an unidentified administration official, said Reno would
oppose the bill at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's bill says any government official who
''knowingly and willfully discloses ... any classified
information'' to an unauthorized individual is guilty of a felony
and may be fined up to $10,000 and imprisoned for up to three
years, Shelby was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0109 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storms Swamp North Dakota  </HEADLINE>
By MATT GOURAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILBY, N.D. (AP) -- Crews from the Grand Forks Air Force Base
arrived in this eastern North Dakota community to help save homes
from flooding after storms that dumped more than a foot of rain in
12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   One man was dead and another missing after a car drove into a
washout late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency shelters were set up as people in Gilby and other
small towns along the Turtle River fought the rising water.
</P>
<P>
   ''What are you going to do? If it comes, it comes,'' said Jackie
Irish, who was helping pile sandbags in Gilby, 13 miles northwest
of Grand Forks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said parts of Grand Forks County got between 6 inches
and 10 inches of rain from Monday's storms. One report from an
observer's rain gauge near Larimore, west of Grand Forks, tallied
17 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really incredible -- almost like a year's worth of rain in
a 12-hour period,'' said Dave Kellenbenz, a National Weather
Service meteorologist in Grand Forks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dickson, who farms near Gilby, said he lost about half of
his crop to flooding Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is much worse than in '97,'' he said. ''This happening
here to this town now is like the Dow Jones dropping 5,000
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilby rancher Ron Amundson said he got nearly 15 inches of rain
on his farm, and could not get to his pasture to look after his
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a boat to get out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty people from the Grand Forks Air Base were brought in
Tuesday to help with the sandbagging, said Jim Campbell, Grand
Forks County's emergency manager.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will save that town,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine miles away, residents in Mekinock fled ahead of rising
water. In nearby Manvel, the Turtle River was expected to rise
nearly 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll try and fight and save their homes, but if they see
that they're in danger, they're going to leave,'' said Jim Brink,
an American Red Cross worker.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Forks County sheriff's office said the body of Anthony
Schneider, 25, of Larimore, was recovered in a station wagon that
went into a washout northwest of the town late Monday night. A
26-year-old man who had accompanied Schneider was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Jiacoma of Gilby had to be rescued from his home by boat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both our cars are under water in the shed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Brusegaard, a Gilby farmer and volunteer firefighter, said
many basements were flooded by the storm. He said the rain also
washed out a 30- to 40-yard section of Burlington Northern-Santa Fe
railroad tracks south of Gilby. Workers were trying to repair a
washed-out railroad bridge nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Grand Forks itself, which was ravaged by flooding
and fire in 1997, was in no danger, officials said. It got only
about 2 inches of rain from Monday's storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
