<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lawyer Picked For Clinton Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A lawyer has been selected to argue for President
Clinton's disbarment over his testimony about his relationship with Monica
Lewinksy. Attorney Marie-Bernarde Miller will represent the state panel that
disciplines lawyers in its disbarment petition in circuit court in Little Rock.
Miller said Tuesday that she was hired June 7 but referred all other questions
about the case to the state Supreme Court Committee on Professional Conduct. The
committee recommended May 22 that Clinton be stripped of his license to practice
law in Arkansas over misleading testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
case about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
3 Killed in Sri Lankan Bus Explosion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A suicide bomber rammed his bicycle into a bus
carrying 25 military troops Wednesday, killing himself and two civilians on a
highway that links the capital with the international airport, witnesses and
police said. The suicide bomber and two passers-by were killed and another six
civilians were injured, police said. None of the air force soldiers were hurt,
police said. Police blamed the explosion on the Tamil Tiger rebels fighting a
separatist war since 1983 to establish an independent homeland for the Tamil
minority.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House GOP Seeks $16M for Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- House Republican leaders will demand GOP lawmakers raise
$16 million for use in key contested races this fall, officials said Tuesday
night. They intend to hold the rank and file accountable through control of
chairmanships and committee assignments in 2001. Any Republican who declines to
assume responsibility for his allotted fund-raising quota will be asked to
''call the speaker (House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.), set up a personal
meeting to tell him why,'' according to material prepared for a session of GOP
members on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suharto Family Negotiating With Govt.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Indonesia's president said Tuesday that family members of
former autocratic President Suharto are negotiating with the government to
return any alleged ill-gotten gains from the years of Suharto's rule. The family
''would like to give back the fortune ... to the state,'' President Abdurrahman
Wahid said during a speech to the American Indonesian Chamber of Commerce in New
York. He said negotiations are under way. Suharto's family and lawyers could not
immediately be reached for comment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Found Guilty in Xerox Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A former Xerox copier repairman was convicted Tuesday of
gunning down seven co-workers in Hawaii's worst mass killing. A jury found Byran
Uyesugi, 40, guilty of first-degree murder, which covers multiple killings, and
attempted murder in the second degree for shooting at an eighth co-worker and
missing. The verdict means the jury believes Uyesugi was legally sane during his
Nov. 2 shooting spree at a Xerox parts warehouse.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Change in Release of Census Data Sought
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Secretary Richard Daley will propose giving the
head of the Census Bureau the final say on when to make public sampled census
data that could drastically affect the way congressional district lines are
redrawn, Census officials said Tuesday. The authority to release the
statistically adjusted data from Census 2000 currently lies with the commerce
secretary. The announcement of the proposal will come at a news conference
Wednesday, Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said Tuesday night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Number of Refugees Grows Worldwide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Conflicts in Kosovo and East Timor and wars across
Africa sent 7 million people fleeing their homes last year, bringing to 35
million the number of people worldwide who are uprooted and in need of
protection, a leading refugee organization said Tuesday. The U.S. Committee for
Refugees said more people were living in refugee camps and makeshift housing at
the end of this decade than at the start. In 1990, 29 million people were either
refugees -- defined as people forced to flee their countries -- or internally
displaced residents who leave their homes but not their countries to escape
fighting or political instability.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday on profit-taking in light
trading. The Nikkei shed 152.25 points, or 0.90 percent, to 16,762.70 in the
first 30 minutes of trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox 5, Yankees 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jason Varitek homered into the upper deck off Orlando
Hernandez and the Boston bullpen shut down the New York Yankees on one hit for 6
2-3 innings, giving the Red Sox a 5-3 victory Tuesday night. Carl Everett
contributed a triple, double and single as the Red Sox moved into a virtual
first-place tie with the Yankees in the AL East.
</P>
