<DOCNO> APW20000614.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Concerned About UAW Holiday  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN AFFLECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Election Day this November will be a holiday
for some 400,000 autoworkers, and that has Republicans concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday, written into major United Auto Worker contracts for
this year and 2002, will make it easier for those workers to vote --
and to help in get-out-the-vote efforts. And they're mostly in the
Midwest where close contests in big states could end up deciding
the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Republican Chairman Robert Bennett said, ''It certainly
puts us at a competitive disadvantage for the volunteers needed for
Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't really, exactly happy when you put 400,000 additional
Democratic grass-roots people in the field -- although let me say
I'm well aware that the Republicans are getting about 40 percent of
the labor vote and we'll appeal to pro-Republican union members,''
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss Center for Applied
Politics at the University of Akron, said having more autoworkers
voting and volunteering on Nov. 7 could have a major impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''The UAW workers will make the most difference where the
election is the closest, where there is a 2 to 3 percent
difference,'' Green said. ''And the industrial Midwest will be very
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The holiday provision was written into contracts the United Auto
Workers agreed to last year with the Big Three automakers and
Delphi Automotive System. About 400,000 UAW members nationwide work
for the Big Three -- General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler -- and
for Delphi, GM's former parts unit, the union says.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest totals are for Michigan, Ohio and Indiana, with
substantial numbers for Missouri, Wisconsin, New York and Illinois,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Gov. John Engler ''considers this the largest soft
money contribution in American political history,'' said John
Truscott, a spokesman for the Republican governor. ''Companies will
have to pay salary and benefits for them to go out and campaign for
Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Democratic Chairman David Leland sees things differently.
He says the Republican concerns suggest the GOP is ''afraid of the
electorate. I think anything we can do to encourage voter
participation helps the democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the idea of taking Election Day off is to
increase voter turnout -- not to help a particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not about Democrat and Republican -- it's about people.
Getting people in the right place on the right day,'' said Willie
Hubbard, president of UAW Local 1250, in suburban Cleveland, which
represents 4,200 workers at a Ford engine plant.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krell, communications director for the UAW at its Detroit
headquarters, agreed. ''Many countries have their election days off
and most countries have a much higher voter participation than we
do,'' he said. ''It's not about partisanship, it's about
citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has not endorsed Gore, and its president Stephen Yokich,
said the union should consider alternatives such as Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader after Gore backed normalizing trade relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bennett, the Ohio Republican chairman, said union leaders
and the Democratic Party are ''synonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he, too, strongly supports voter participation but
doesn't like one party getting an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has suggested the Republicans include making Election
Day a national holiday in their party platform this summer.
</P>
<P>
   That idea doesn't seem to have received much attention from the
GOP at a national level. A Republican National Committee
spokeswoman working on party platform issues hadn't heard of
Bennett's idea when asked about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0208 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus With Sri Lankan Troops Explodes  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A suicide bomber rammed his bicycle
into a bus carrying 25 military troops Wednesday, killing himself
and two civilians on a highway that links the capital with the
international airport, witnesses and police said.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide bomber and two passers-by were killed and another
six civilians were injured, police said. None of the air force
soldiers were hurt, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police blamed the explosion on the Tamil Tiger rebels fighting a
separatist war since 1983 to establish an independent homeland for
the Tamil minority.
</P>
<P>
   The male bomber attacked the bus at Wattala, about six miles
north of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
   An evasive action by the bus driver minimized the impact as the
blast damaged the rear portion of the vehicle. ''He managed to
swerve his vehicle, thus not allowing the bomber to hit the target
properly,'' said Defense Ministry spokesman Brig. Palitha Fernando.
</P>
<P>
   A witness, Arun Roy, said he was several cars behind the bus
when it exploded just after 7 a.m. north of Colombo on the road to
Bandaranaike International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''I suddenly heard a loud explosion,'' he said. ''I saw car
tires and vehicle tires and bodies flying.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been blamed for a series of suicide bombings and
other attacks in the capital, including a suicide bombing last week
that killed a Cabinet minister and 22 others.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers are posted at checkpoints throughout the capital and
other cities to guard against terrorist attacks, while 40,000
government troops are fighting the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
for control of the northern Jaffna Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have cut off land access to the peninsula, forcing
the government to supply its troops on the peninsula by air and
sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
