<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Media CEO Godfrey Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Paul Godfrey has resigned as chief executive
officer of Sun Media Corp., to be replaced on an interim basis by
former Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, 61, made the announcement to the newspaper's staff
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel that I have accomplished at the Sun what I set out to
do and I want to explore new and exciting challenges,'' he said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mulroney temporarily adds the CEO title to his position as
chairman of the board of Sun Media. The search for a permanent
successor begins immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Media, taken over by Montreal-based newspaper and printing
giant Quebecor Inc. in January 1999, is the second-largest
newspaper company in Canada in terms of circulation, behind the
Southam group owned by Hollinger Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey will remain on the Sun Media board, and said he will
continue to work to bring a National Football League franchise to
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   A chemical engineer by training, Godfrey spent almost two
decades in municipal politics before becoming publisher of the
Toronto Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Under Godfrey, the Sun group grew from four newspapers to
include eight metro dailies, eight community dailies and 174 weekly
newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
