<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paterson family filed federal lawsuit against school district  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The parents of a Paterson boy have filed a
federal lawsuit against the school district, claiming the learning
disabled student was deprived of his right to a ''free and
appropriate education'' because the district did not enter him into
special education.
</P>
<P>
   According to a complaint filed last month in U.S. District Court
here, the student, now 19, was first diagnosed with ''receptive and
expressive language delays'' when he was 3.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his education, speech pathologists at St. Joseph's
Hospital and Medical Center and the district's own psychologists
re-evaluated him, finding that he had limited verbal skills and
difficulty understanding information. They recommended special
education.
</P>
<P>
   But the Paterson Board of Education ignored those reports until
he turned 17, according to Mary Hartnett, an attorney at the
Rutgers Special Education Clinic in Newark, who is representing the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The student received failing grades throughout grammar school,
but continued to be promoted into high school. When his mother
voiced concern, teachers told her the student was doing fine,
Hartnett said.
</P>
<P>
   After a social worker intervened in 1997, the student was
reclassified as ''educable mentally retarded.'' In 1999, the school
board agreed to pay for his education at a private school in Bergen
County, where he is performing at the third-grade level, Hartnett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We filed the lawsuit because we didn't think any amount of
education would make up for all the years he lost,'' Hartnett told
the Herald and News of West Paterson for Wednesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The student's identity, as well as that of the parents, was kept
confidential in the lawsuit. The family is also suing a series of
school officials who evaluated their son or participated in his
education - including former state commissioners of education,
school superintendents, principals, teachers and psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gillman, an attorney for the Paterson school board,
declined to comment on the case until the district files a formal
response.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our preliminary investigation indicates that the district
expects to be denying the charges,'' Gillman said. ''Regardless of
the litigation, the district is working with the child and his
parents to give him an appropriate education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
