<HEADLINE> Doctor's license revoked by state Health Department  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - The medical license of a Chautauqua
County doctor has been revoked following charges of moral unfitness
and willful abuse of patients.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Health Department's Professional Medical
Conduct office, Dr. Dan G. Alexander fondled patients on more than
one occasion and improperly filed medical records.
</P>
<P>
   In a 37-page review, the board said the obvious penalty for
Alexander was revocation of his license. The respondent must be
punished for heinous and immoral patient abuse, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the patients to testify against Alexander was Debra Kost,
from Frewsburg in Chautauqua County, who along with her husband,
Robert, filed a multimillion dollar lawsuit against the doctor in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   She became his patient on Nov. 6, 1995, and later accused
Alexander of overmedicating her and of sexual molestation. The
Kosts dropped their lawsuit earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kost said she was happy the state found Alexander guilty of
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Barber of the Albany law firm Murphy, Burns, Barber and
Murphy, who represented Alexander during the hearings, said an
aggressive appeal was planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
