<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Moving Through Pentagon Bills  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to pay for Pentagon programs next
year is advancing in Congress with Senate passage of a $287.4
billion spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the measure, one of 13 appropriations bills
needed to keep the government functioning after next Oct. 1, by a
lopsided 95-3 vote Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It now goes to a House-Senate conference panel, which will
reconcile it with the House version passed last week, which is
roughly $1 billion higher.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions include a 3.7 percent military pay raise, $4.6
million for continued development of a missile defense system and
funds for buying 10 F-22 Raptor aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate was turning to separate legislation
dealing with Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   Before approving the spending bill, the Senate rejected, on a
65-32 vote, an amendment by Sens. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., that would have stopped the Pentagon from leasing
more executive jets for its top brass.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon already leases six executive jets and wants $48.6
million for six more, Harkin said. ''There is no justification for
additional luxury jets to ferry generals and admirals around from
meeting to meeting,'' said Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, said the leasing program was an attempt to save taxpayers
money ''to lease aircraft instead of replacing them,'' as do ''most
major businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final 95-3 vote, Sens. Boxer, Russ Feingold, D-Wis., and
Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., were the ''no'' votes. Not voting were
Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Senate approved another amendment by Boxer that
would restrict the Pentagon's use of powerful pesticides on
installations where there are children.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill is a $3 billion increase over the Clinton
administration request.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, suggested he may
seek to withhold aid to Israel -- or at least delay it -- to protest
Israel's decision to sell advance radar to China.
</P>
<P>
   His panel considers the legislation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is building an aircraft for China and equipping it with
the U.S.-developed PHALCON airborne early warning radar system at a
cost of $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan previously suggested that $2.8 billion in aid to Israel
be cut by that $250 million. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
earlier this week voiced opposition to any such linkage.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Callahan said that he would propose instead to hold
up the early disbursement of Israel's aid money for the time being.
Israel traditionally gets the money up front, in the first two
weeks of each new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   He said that would ''give the administration time to negotiate
what we hope will be an acceptable result.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave the administration a possible way out, saying that if
Secretary of Defense William Cohen ''wants to issue a statement
saying it's not a threat to our national security, then the issue
is over with.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The Senate defense appropriations bill is S. 2593 and can
be found on http://thomas.loc.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0224 </TRAILER>
