<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys' Daryl Johnston To Retire  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Two days after Steve Young walked away from
football to protect his health, Dallas Cowboys fullback Daryl
Johnston is doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston scheduled a news conference for 2 p.m. Wednesday at
Texas Stadium to announce he's leaving the game rather than take
any more hits on his fragile neck.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's rugged blocking opened holes for Emmitt Smith and
protected Troy Aikman as the Cowboys won Super Bowl titles
following the 1992, '93 and '95 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, those same hits ultimately led to a herniated disc in
his neck that cut short his 1997 season after six games, then
limited him to one game last season, his 11th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston has been expected to retire since doctors discovered
those complications.
</P>
<P>
   His retirement will save the team about $544,000 toward the
salary cap this season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston and Young are both represented by agent Leigh
Steinberg, who has encouraged players to walk away while still
healthy enough to enjoy life after football.
</P>
<P>
   By running behind Johnston, Smith became one of the NFL's most
prolific runners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's definitely the best -- he was for me,'' Smith
said. ''He can handle his own against anyone else in the league. I
think he's done a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston became a fan favorite throughout the NFL. Stadiums
across the country roared his nickname ''Moose'' whenever he got a
rare carry or caught a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's grunt work was so appreciated that the Pro Bowl began
inviting true fullbacks and picked him in 1993 and '94, the first
two years under the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas picked Johnston in the second round of the 1989 draft,
after making Aikman the No. 1 overall pick. Johnston played 149
straight games before undergoing surgery six weeks into the 1997
season to fuse two vertebrae in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to play every game in '98, then lasted only one week
into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For his career, Johnston had 753 yards rushing and 2,227 yards
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   The departures of Johnston and Deion Sanders further distances
Dallas from its NFL champion teams of the mid-1990s -- with one more
loss likely to come.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Michael Irvin also is expected to retire because of a
neck problem. However, he is not under contract, so he is facing no
deadline to decide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0226 </TRAILER>
