<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea of Cortez To Be Preserved  </HEADLINE>
By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- A. Bates Butler III has been fishing for 30
years in Mexico's Sea of Cortez, once teeming with grouper,
hammerhead sharks, yellowfin tuna, barracuda and manta rays.
</P>
<P>
   Exploited and overfished, the sea -- also known as the Gulf of
California -- is now in danger of becoming barren. Butler, a former
U.S. attorney, and a group of Arizonans and Sonorans have formed a
nonprofit organization to help Mexico preserve its marine
resources.
</P>
<P>
   They'll discuss the sea's precarious health and urge Mexico to
create a Sonora Marine Park near Guaymas, Mexico, when the
Arizona-Mexico Commission meets here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't see the sailfish that we used to see, we don't see
the marlin, the dorado are down. We haven't caught a tuna in the
last two summers,'' said Butler, a member of the commission. ''And
if something isn't done soon to protect the natural resources -- the
fish and other sea life -- there will not be a commercial fishing
industry and there will not be a sports fishing industry or a dive
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say commercial fishing in the sea has overharvested many
species, particularly through tuna boats that employ miles-long
baited lines or so-called gill nets, indiscriminately snaring and
killing marlin, dorado and sailfish as well as tuna.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is not with the fishing but the way it's being
done,'' said Francis Gilbert, development director for the Sonoran
Sea Aquarium being planned in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, too many small shrimping boats, and commercial
shrimp farming, have placed intense pressure on the shellfish. Some
mangrove swamps or estuaries -- critical natural habitat for shrimp,
crabs, fish and plant life -- have been eliminated by commercial
shrimp farms and by development.
</P>
<P>
   Mangrove trees are cut for wood, and polluted waste waters
discharged from shrimp farms alter the brackish water's delicate
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main problems are the economical problems of this
country,'' said Artemisa Castro, a marine resource management
scientist in Guaymas who has spent her last 15 years focusing on
the Sea of Cortez. Until early this year, she ran Mexico's National
Shrimp Research Program in Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   ''Possible destruction of some species is only an environmental
consequence, but the real cause is our economic policies which
drive us to different management strategies,'' she said. ''It has a
lot to do with the society and the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions mean the long-term future of the sea is being
sacrificed for the immediate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to make things change,'' Castro said. ''Things will
never change from top to bottom, they have to change from bottom to
top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0237 </TRAILER>
