<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad Buried in Home Village  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- World leaders brought to Syria by death
took time for the Mideast peace process, holding talks alongside
the funeral services for Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright bowed her head briefly
before Assad's casket Tuesday and then conferred privately with
Bashar Assad, the heir apparent of the president who died Saturday
at 69, for about 20 minutes. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who
had quarreled bitterly with Assad, saluted before the coffin, then
kissed the son, clasping his hand and speaking for a few moments.
</P>
<P>
   Albright emerged with a pledge from Bashar Assad to stick close
to his father's line on peace talks with Israel. Little more could
be expected of Assad's son, who at this stage must step carefully
while shoring up his support base.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral, Assad was laid to rest Tuesday in the tiny
mountain village of Qardaha. Thousands of people converged outside
the mosque Assad built to honor his mother in his hometown, 125
miles northwest of Damascus. The soldier-pallbearers struggled to
keep mourners from pushing forward to kiss the flag-draped coffin,
trying to create order so prayers for the dead could begin.
</P>
<P>
   ''His death is a national catastrophe,'' said Hafez al-Shuraiqi,
69, a former schoolmate of the president. ''Qardaha is proud of its
son. He was a great man, loyal to his friends, loyal to his country
and loyal to his ideals. I shall miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   After prayers at the mosque, Hafez Assad was entombed next to
his eldest son Basil in a grand mausoleum on a hill overlooking
Qardaha. Basil Assad died in a 1994 car crash, and it was then that
Assad began grooming Bashar to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad was meeting Albright and several high-level
visitors for the first time Tuesday. Others he had met before on
trips in the region as his father's envoy.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac greeted Bashar Assad warmly. The
two met in November when Bashar Assad traveled to France on his
first trip outside the Arab world on an errand for his father.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also met with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa met with al-Sharaa on Tuesday,
saying their talks focused on relations between the two nations and
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's longtime leader committed himself to negotiations when
he joined multilateral peace talks in Madrid in 1991. But little
progress has been made on the Syria-Israel track since then.
</P>
<P>
   The United States managed to revive those talks last year, but
they stalled in January. Syria wanted assurances that Israel would
withdraw from the Golan Heights and withdraw to borders from before
the 1967 Mideast war in which Israel won the strategic plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Israel refused to make such a pledge and insisted that security
and normalization issues be spelled out first.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, in Luxembourg for a meeting
with European Union foreign ministers, said he hopes a new Syrian
president will opt for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it will be in Syria's interest to continue with
the policy they have followed for the past 30 years,'' Levy said
Tuesday. ''We hope a new, young president ... will choose peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria's longing for the Golan was underscored even amid the
mourning. Among the dignitaries at the funeral was Hassan
Nasrallah, whose Hezbollah guerrillas took credit for pushing
Israeli troops from south Lebanon three weeks ago. When Nasrallah
arrived at the palace where Assad lay in state, the Syria TV
announcer said, ''Thank God you saw the south (of Lebanon)
liberated ... We will liberate our Golan, God willing.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad's funeral also brought about scenes reminiscent of feuding
relatives' calling a truce after a death in the family.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat had a greeting kiss for Syrian Defense Minister Mustafa
Tlass, who less than a year ago called Arafat ''the son of 60,000
whores'' for making concessions to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's relationship with Syria, where many rival Palestinian
factions are based, has been hostile for years because Assad viewed
Arafat as failing to be steadfast against Israel. But with the
possibility of a final Palestinian-Israeli deal, many regional
equations are being rethought.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat stopped on the way to the palace for a brief meeting with
Nayef Hawatmeh, head of the Damascus-based Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine. The DFLP was one of the staunchest
opponents of reconciliation with Israel in the 1970s, but recently
renounced violence in favor of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In one sign of rifts not mended, however, Rifaat Assad made his
own claim to power even before his estranged brother was buried.
Rifaat, who has been in exile in Europe since attempting to seize
power in 1983, told The Associated Press in Beirut through a
spokesman that he planned to return to Damascus at the
''appropriate time'' to contest his nephew's leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0238 </TRAILER>
