<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad's Uncle Has Little Backing  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATAKIA, Syria (AP) -- Rifaat Assad once had a following here.
But no more.
</P>
<P>
   The home region of the late President Hafez Assad rallied around
his son and all-but-certain successor Bashar Assad on Tuesday,
rejecting the claim by Assad's exiled brother Rifaat that he is the
rightful heir.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot even say that man's name,'' said Nizam Nameh, a
48-year-old engineer in Qardaha, the Assads' home village outside
the northern port city of Latakia. ''Instead of coming here to give
his condolences, he is speaking such trash. Bashar has our full
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The feud erupted on the eve of Assad's funeral when Rifaat, who
has been banished since 1984 and stripped of all official posts,
said through a spokesman he would return to Syria and challenge
Bashar's claim to leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's ruling Baath Party, the parliament and the military all
have thrown their support behind Bashar Assad, whom his father had
groomed to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear where Rifaat, who has been living in Europe, was
Tuesday as his brother was being buried. Reports said Syrian
officials have ordered Rifaat's arrest if he tries to return.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Syrians appear to be backing Bashar as well.
</P>
<P>
   Imad Ballan, a 42-year-old shopowner in Latakia, admitted he
felt initial alarm when he heard Rifaat was planning to return. But
Ballan, wearing black mourning clothes and carrying a picture of
Bashar Assad, soon shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter. He has no following, no popular base,'' he
said. ''Nobody takes him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old Rifaat made his reputation as a loyal and
ruthless enforcer for his brother. In 1982, he led crack army units
in an assault that crushed an uprising by Muslim fundamentalists in
the northern city of Hama. The death toll reportedly came to more
than 20,000, though it was never officially disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   But the next year, as Hafez Assad lay in a hospital recuperating
from a heart attack, Rifaat's tanks began maneuvering on the
streets of Damascus in moves that were seen as an attempted coup.
Relations between the brothers rapidly cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Rifaat's latest threats to seize power, authorities
were moving against him. In October, army troops cracked down on
his supporters in Latakia, reportedly resulting in hundreds being
killed and wounded. Syrian officials never commented, but Rifaat's
military power base was believed to have been dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his estrangement, Rifaat has returned to Syria for other
family funerals. In 1992 he came for the burial of the family
matriarch, Na'isa. And he returned for the 1994 funeral of Basil
Assad, the president's eldest son who died in a traffic accident --
spoiling Assad's hopes that his firstborn would succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   In Qardaha, retired Brig. Ali Sfeir, 59, said most in the area
saw Rifaat Assad's claim to power as baseless.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Assad gave us stability,'' he said. ''It's an
inheritance we will not squander.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0239 </TRAILER>
