<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Team Survives in Tenn. City  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) -- When Lincoln Ziyenge says he'll do almost
anything to play soccer, he means it.
</P>
<P>
   The man who grew up playing with a plastic bottle stuffed with
newspaper as a soccer ball makes the four-hour trip from
Huntsville, Ala., at least three times a week to play for the
Tennessee Rhythm of the United Soccer Leagues.
</P>
<P>
   And to keep his amateur status, the Zimbabwe native does it for
free -- not even gas money for his Oldsmobile, which is pushing
150,000 miles after a year of commuting.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just the circumstances that I have to deal with for the
love of the game,'' said Ziyenge, who is working on a marketing
degree at the University of Alabama-Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Love of the game is the only reason the Rhythm, the oldest
franchise in the USL, still exists in a city where the NFL's
Tennessee Titans, the NHL's Nashville Predators and Southeastern
Conference collegiate teams attract most sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rhythm began as the Nashville Metros in 1989, the team
was only the second professional franchise in the city. The other
was the Triple-A Nashville Sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Metros worked their way up the USL ladder and spent years
getting a contract with the city and a home field.
</P>
<P>
   Just when they felt established, two of the team's owners
withdrew their financial support last year three weeks before the
season started.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing not to give up, general manager Devinder Sandhu and
original partner Lynn Agee found two more partners, asked a player
to serve as coach, then recruited new players to the 25-member
team.
</P>
<P>
   They also moved to a new field at Battle Ground Academy, a
private prep school 14 miles south of Nashville, and renamed the
team the Tennessee Rhythm -- playing off Nashville's notoriety as
the capital of country music.
</P>
<P>
   Few thought the patchwork team would win a game, but the Rhythm
went 11-17.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're like Jason from the horror movie,'' said Sandhu, an
engineer and former Vanderbilt University soccer player. ''You
never know if we're dead. We just keep coming back and coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Brett Mosen, the team's coach in 1995, was hired back for
the current season, which runs through September.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a challenging job without a doubt, with the type of
players we're having to bring in, obviously with less experience,''
he said. ''But that's something I'm quite prepared to step up to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rhythm play in the A-League, just a step below Major League
Soccer. MLS teams can borrow A-League players, and the Colorado
Rapids did just that with midfielder Danny Devall this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee plays the Dallas Burn on June 14 in the second round
of the U.S. Open Cup, a competition open to everyone from church
teams to MLS members.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking at it as an opportunity to prove there's not
such a huge gap as people believe been MLS and A-League,'' Mosen
said.
</P>
<P>
   But beating the Burn might be easier than the winning over more
fans in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans and Predators attract most of the attention. The
Sounds and the Nashville Kats of the Arena Football League get the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhythm average about 1,000 fans per home game in Franklin, a
city in Tennessee's richest county and where youth soccer has grown
in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials are trying free passes, an Internet site and
advertisements geared at groups that follow non-traditional sports,
but game attendance remains low.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors could help, too, but those also are difficult
to get, president Dan Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the sponsorship money has just about been absorbed by the
Predators, Titans and the Kats,'' Lucas said. ''We cannot compete
with those types of organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rhythm will continue to use the personal touch.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are invited onto the field after games to meet players and
get autographs. Teams can get personal lessons from a player or
coach for a negotiable fee.
</P>
<P>
   It's a labor of love for players like Ziyenge, who coaches
Alabama-Huntsville's women's soccer team to make ends meet. Only
the coach and two other team officials get full-time salaries, so
most players work full-time jobs around their practice and game
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   That proves tricky when there's a game in San Diego or
Vancouver, but Ziyenge says it's worth the hassle and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my favorite game and I would do almost anything to get to
play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http:www.rhythmsoccer.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 0239 </TRAILER>
