<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Messier, Lemieux, Tocchet Available  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Columbus Blue Jackets and Minnesota Wild
will get a chance to pick up a six-time Stanley Cup champion: Mark
Messier.
</P>
<P>
   Messier was left unprotected Tuesday by the Vancouver Canucks
and is available to the newest expansion teams when they stock
their rosters at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   If chosen, Messier might never play with the first-year teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't change our hope to sign him and it doesn't change
our desire to get him back,'' Canucks general manager Brian Burke
said. ''I don't think it was logical to protect him and certainly
lose a player.''
</P>
<P>
   With two years left on a contract scheduled to pay $6 million
per season, the 39-year-old Messier doesn't fit the mold of young,
inexpensive players typically targeted by expansion teams.
</P>
<P>
   If either the Wild or Blue Jackets select Messier during the
June 23 draft, they inherit the remaining two seasons on his
existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   The teams would also assume an option to buy out those two years
for $2 million and a no-trade clause that gives Messier power over
his future destinations.
</P>
<P>
   If he's not chosen, the Canucks intend to buy him out and hope
to sign him as a free agent at a reduced cost.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't make the day any less exciting for Blue Jackets GM
Doug MacLean.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was sitting at a Tim Horton's at 4:30 this morning, looking
at the list,'' said MacLean, who called it a huge day for the
franchise that will begin play next season. ''Either I'm going
goofy or I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus, which won a coin flip, has priority in the expansion
draft and has the choice of where each team will pick in the
four-round process.
</P>
<P>
   Three goalies will be selected by each team in the first round,
followed by eight defensemen each in the second, 13 forwards each
in the third and two additional selections per club in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean said the list was fairly close to what his staff
projected.
</P>
<P>
   Potential free agents available are more likely to be taken than
high-priced veterans, MacLean said, because of their compensation
value should they sign with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone on the lists is really available. Many side deals
have already been consummated to ensure that certain players won't
be lost by their current clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Doug Gilmour is one of those cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no issue there,'' Gilmour's agent Larry Kelly said.
''They've (the Sabres) made a deal and he won't be picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour, who will turn 37 later this month, intends to retire
after next season.
</P>
<P>
   Each team, excluding Nashville and Atlanta, which began play in
1998 and 1999, respectively, can lose up to two players. The
Predators and Thrashers won't lose anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux, who helped New Jersey win its second Stanley Cup
this season, was among 22 Devils left unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean said he would like to add a veteran goalie to go along
with 22-year-old Marc Denis. Denis, the understudy to Patrick Roy,
was acquired from Colorado for the Blue Jackets' second-round pick
in the league's entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like a veteran to start off with, but it's got to be
the right combination for us,'' MacLean said. ''Denis is our future
at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's John Vanbiesbrouck is one player that might fit
the bill. MacLean was his coach in 1996 when the Florida Panthers
advanced to the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sure what's going to happen with John,'' MacLean said
of the Flyers goalie, who lost his starting spot to rookie Brian
Boucher. ''He has an option on his contract in the $3 million-plus
range. So I'll see what happens with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other available players include defensemen Marty McSorley
(Boston), Paul Coffey (Carolina), and Sylvain Cote (Dallas).
McSorley is still under indefinite suspension for his stick attack
against Vancouver's Donald Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   Available forwards include Bob Probert (Chicago), Guy Carbonneau
(Dallas), Joe Kocur and Igor Larionov (Detroit), Dave Andreychuk
(Colorado), Stephane Richer (St. Louis), and Wendel Clark
(Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau, the NHL's oldest player at 40, has been mulling
front office offers and his return to the ice is still
undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Fuhr (Calgary), Tom Barrasso (Ottawa) and Sean Burke
(Phoenix) are prominent goalies left unprotected. But Fuhr has
indicated he will retire.
</P>
<P>
   Teams were able to protect either up to five defensemen, nine
forwards and one goalie, or up to three defensemen, seven forwards
and two goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the exposed forwards had to be under contract for next
season and must have played in either 40 games last season or 70
over the previous two.
</P>
<P>
   Through trades and signings of free agents, the Blue Jackets
have 16 players under contract heading into the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're an expansion team and we have a long way to go, but I
feel pretty good where we are,'' MacLean said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
