<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silicon Valley Faces Housing Crunch  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE M. PETERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The ''New Economy'' has all but
eliminated ''housing bargain'' from the lexicon throughout the San
Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Stephen Gray, whose $850,000 offer for a three-bedroom
home lost out to someone who bid twice the asking price. Said Gray:
''It's emotionally wrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay area houses sell so quickly buyers take risks that would be
unheard of elsewhere. Some make offers based on a 15-minute glimpse
at an open house and others bid as much as $200,000 above the
asking price. Some even are willing to buy a home ''as is'' --
without inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ''You go through a process where you lose deal after deal and
deal -- and you're willing to do anything to get in,'' said Andrew
La Mont, a real estate agent for Coldwell Banker.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the housing market has been transformed by the new
dot-com economy. The nation's strong job production in well-paid,
high-tech jobs has driven up the home prices at twice the rate of
inflation, according to the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's State of the Cities 2000 report, released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, 21 of 25 metropolitan areas that are top high-tech
markets had rent increases greater than inflation. Rents surged by
more than 20 percent between 1995 and 1999 in Denver and the San
Francisco Bay area while they rose by more than 15 percent in
Boston, Kansas City, Atlanta, Seattle, San Diego and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, San Francisco has the most expensive housing market,
followed by Honolulu, Los Angeles, New York City, San Diego and
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco also is California's least affordable housing
market, with only 10 percent of buyers able to afford the $538,732,
median-priced home. The national affordability rate is 52 percent,
according to a report released this month by the California
Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding wars have put median-priced homes for sale today beyond
the reach of 84 percent of Bay Area residents, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of future wealth through stock options won't pay
mortgages in Silicon Valley, where a one-bedroom cottage can cost
$800,000, or San Francisco, where two-bedroom homes start at half a
million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get a lot of referrals from people looking to move here
because of work and they're already priced out of the market before
they even get here,'' La Mont said.
</P>
<P>
   With so many tech workers competing for so few homes,
middle-class Old Economy workers -- teachers, firefighters,
accountants -- are priced entirely out of the market, said Jeannie
Anderson, president of the San Francisco Realtors Association.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco school district has taken a novel approach to
try and lure teachers. The district recently announced it would
build affordable, teacher-only apartments, with HUD's assistance.
Ground breaking is scheduled for September.
</P>
<P>
   Humble neighborhoods across the bay in Oakland, Fremont and
Hayward no longer offer bargains. Even in East Palo Alto, once
labeled the murder capital of the world, the median price for an
average, single-family home was $325,000 in February -- up from
$215,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and Doreen Martinez were among the lucky few to grab a
new home in South San Francisco. New homes are a rarity in the
region that most available land, even the steepest hillsides, is
already developed.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they had the preview, 3,000 to 5,000 people showed up,''
Doreen Martinez said. ''It felt like a rock concert. People had to
park in dirt lots then stand in line to get into the model homes.''
</P>
<P>
   They were put on a waiting list but eventually got their home
after a lengthy appeals process. They wouldn't say what they paid,
but said the four-bedroom home has appreciated about $100,000 since
they moved in last December.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, it was worth it, because we got what we wanted,''
Daniel Martinez said. ''But that's it for us. We'll be in this
house for the rest of our lives -- we're not moving again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
