<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Book Chronicles the Holocaust  </HEADLINE>
By DEBRA HALE SHELTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- It was 1945. The war had just ended, and Jewish
immigrants were moving into Louis Weber's West Side neighborhood.
Through the eyes of this 9-year-old Jewish boy, something was
disturbingly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was stunned by their faces,'' Weber recalled years later.
''They looked deadened, empty. The people had numbers tattooed on
their arms, and I didn't know why. I knew the families of these
newcomers, but no one would tell me anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust survivors' story eventually was told, over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   Weber, the son of Polish Jews who came to America in the early
1920s, could not forget the atrocities. Nor could he forget the
struggles of his own parents, who left for Canada and later the
United States when the Russian army was plundering Jewish villages
and killing tens of thousands in Poland and the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Weber decided to use his resources as the head of a
thriving publishing company to help keep the story alive ''so that
all those people who died didn't die in vain.'' He recently
published ''The Holocaust Chronicle: A History in Words and
Pictures,'' a not-for-profit book that traces the tragedy from its
origins to its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Weber's company, Publications International Ltd., already has
donated 10,000 copies of the 768-page book, written primarily by
six professors, to schools, synagogues, churches, libraries and
other organizations. More donations are planned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I realized I'm in a unique position to bring the Holocaust
story to a wide audience, as well as to give something back to the
Jewish community,'' the 63-year-old publisher says.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the board of The ''1939'' Club, a Los Angeles-based
organization of Holocaust survivors and their families, honored
Weber and his company with the group's Media Award, which goes to
those who have contributed significantly to an understanding of the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a unique book because it is so user-friendly in
the sense that you don't have to read it cover to cover at one
sitting. ... Each page has a wealth of information,'' says William
Elperin, president of The ''1939'' Club, which gets its name from
the year Adolf Hitler's forces invaded Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Weber sees the book as a legacy to his children and
grandchildren. Their pictures abound in his office in suburban
Lincolnwood, along with scores of books on everything from
Corvettes to cooking to the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The book, checked by a team of Holocaust scholars, includes an
80,000-word timeline of Holocaust-related events covering about
3,000 years of history. Yet even that, the book acknowledges, is
not complete. ''Many facts of the Holocaust died with the
victims,'' the introduction says.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains more than 1,700 pictures, including the cover
picture of a big-eyed, dark-haired little girl discovered by
British troops in the typhus ward of the Bergen-Belsen
concentration camp in Germany in April 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a face that shows apprehension; it shows pride, a hint of
defiance,'' says David Hogan, who as editor-in-chief selected the
picture. The child's name and fate are not known.
</P>
<P>
   The book is accessible. The writing is lively, and both the
words and the pictures put human faces on the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven million people died during the Holocaust. Six million
were Jews. Among other targeted groups were Gypsies, Polish
citizens, Soviet prisoners of war, homosexuals, the handicapped,
Freemasons, Jehovah's Witnesses and other political and religious
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Among the persecuted who appear in the book:
</P>
<P>
   --Mania Halef, a little girl photographed in 1936 in a play suit
with a ribbon in her hair and a doll in her hands. In 1941, the
7-year-old was shot during the Germans' massacre of more than
33,000 Jews at a ravine outside Kiev, Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   --An unidentified boy dressed in rags and bandages and carrying a
tin cup, as he wanders through the streets of Poland's Warsaw
Ghetto. His swollen and splotchy feet and legs are those of an old
man. He stoops as he stares at the camera.
</P>
<P>
   --A group of small children posing for a photographer just before
they are killed. One cries, rubbing her eyes. A few smile, unaware
of their fate. They are among the estimated 1 million Jewish
children who died during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   --An elderly, bearded Orthodox Jew being forcibly shaved for
entertainment by SS troops, a violation of many Eastern European
Jews' religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Weber has helped support Jewish charitable
organizations, but this is his company's first book dealing with
the Holocaust. The company is best known for its cookbooks and
children's books.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures for the Holocaust book were chosen after sifting from
many thousands in the collections of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial
Museum in Washington, D.C., and Yad Vashem in Jerusalem, as well as
other archives and private collections.
</P>
<P>
   The book is available in stores for prices ranging from $16 to
$35.
</P>
<P>
   Publications International's Web site carries the book's entire
text and many of the images. It will be regularly updated with
Holocaust-related developments.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.holocaustchronicle.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
