<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joshua Redman: Leap Into the Beyond  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES J. GANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tenor saxophonist Joshua Redman believes in
taking risks.
</P>
<P>
   That was true nine years ago when, after graduating summa cum
laude from Harvard, he passed up a chance to attend Yale Law School
to become a professional jazz musician. It remains so today with
his newest CD ''Beyond'' (Warner Bros.), whose original tunes take
him into new musical territory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rewards are worth the risk,'' the 31-year-old Redman said.
''I see jazz and art in general as this unfolding process of
constant search and adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Redman had no illusions about the risks involved
in forgoing a career as an Ivy League lawyer to play jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 40 years ago, his father, Dewey Redman, gave up a secure
job as a schoolteacher in Texas to move to California to play jazz.
Although he became one of the most highly regarded tenor
saxophonists on the progressive jazz scene -- working in bands with
Ornette Coleman, Keith Jarrett and Charlie Haden -- he still went
through some lean years.
</P>
<P>
   After his parents separated, Joshua was raised in Berkeley,
Calif., by his mother, Renee Shedroff, a dancer and school
librarian who sometimes had to rely on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   His career has been smoother sailing, and it would be easy for
him to grow complacent and coast on his past successes.
</P>
<P>
   Redman has enjoyed a meteoric rise since winning the prestigious
Thelonious Monk Institute Competition for saxophonists in 1991,
which led to a major record deal with Warner Bros. His seven CDs as
a leader have regularly topped Billboard's traditional jazz charts,
and his quartet steadily tours worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   There have been sponsorship deals with fashion designers such as
Donna Karan and film appearances, most notably in Robert Altman's
''Kansas City,'' in which Redman (as Count Basie band saxophonist
Lester Young) recreates the legendary tenor battles of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   But Redman has not been afraid to risk the opprobrium of jazz
purists by his willingness to embrace other musical genres. He
performed the song ''Waiting on a Friend'' on a Rolling Stones
video -- a piece the rock band originally recorded with one of
Redman's saxophone idols, Sonny Rollins -- and jammed with the Dave
Matthews Band at a concert in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in purity of expression not a purity of style. I've
grown up listening to and loving all kinds of music ... and I've
always felt comfortable allowing everything that I've liked to
influence the way I play jazz,'' Redman said in a telephone
interview from his St. Louis hotel room before a recent concert.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jazz for me is the most inspiring and enjoyable music to play,
but I see the value in all forms of music. For me what's important
is that what I play is truly expressive of what I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   On his previous CD, ''Timeless Tales (For Changing Times),''
released in 1998, Redman set out to break down the barriers between
jazz and the rock, soul and funk he grew up with. He mixed his own
arrangements of jazz standards with completely transformed versions
of more contemporary pop songs by the Beatles, Bob Dylan and Stevie
Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ''What makes these songs 'Timeless Tales' is the openness of the
music,'' Redman said. ''The melodies have to have a power and
presence that are unforgettable ... but the songs can't be too
clearly defined and not leave any room for other interpretations.
... The songs that attract me generally are those that have strong
melodies but also open and suggestive harmonies.''
</P>
<P>
   With ''Timeless Tales,'' Redman seemingly hit on a winning
formula with both critics and the public. But on ''Beyond,'' he
chose a riskier tack by going only with original material.
</P>
<P>
   ''After I finished 'Timeless Tales,' I got immediately inspired
to write a lot of my own music,'' he said. ''There is a different
feeling to the two records, but there are a lot of things in common
... the involvement with complex time signatures, a type of band
fluidity and collective interaction ... and some of the things that
define my sound from a harmonic and melodic standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman says his compositions on ''Beyond'' are more complex than
anything he's written before. But the complexity is balanced by the
strong, simple melodies. That balance is evident right from the
opening track, ''Courage (Asymmetric Aria),'' which is in an odd
13/4 time signature but has a rolling groove.
</P>
<P>
   On ''Beyond,'' Redman stakes out some new musical ground. The
11-minute ''Twilight ... And Beyond'' expands on a musical theme he
originally wrote for Anna Deveare Smith's play ''Twilight,'' about
the Los Angeles riots. It represents Redman's first attempt at an
extended suite-like composition. On ''Leap of Faith,'' with its
intertwining melodic lines, he is joined by fellow tenorman Mark
Turner, marking the first time Redman has invited another horn
player to record on one of his CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't conceive of this as a kind of slash-and-burn tenor
contest,'' Redman said. ''It's about a spirit of communication and
conversation, not a spirit of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman says the heart of the album is the collective spirit of
the quartet he has been able to keep together for the past two
years -- with pianist Aaron Goldberg, bassist Reuben Rogers and
drummer Gregory Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   ''With these compositions and the way this band plays together,
there's really a sense of mapping and charting out some new musical
territory,'' Redman said. ''I definitely feel like musically it's a
step beyond many of the things that I've done before.
</P>
<P>
   ''The music is also expressive of a certain kind of spiritual or
philosophical awareness that I've begun to have over the past
couple of years. It's just a sense I've had that I need to ask
deeper, more probing questions out of life and try to find a way to
lead a meaningful life.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2{ years ago, Redman and his wife Gabrielle Armand, the
director of jazz marketing for Columbia Records, moved from a
Manhattan duplex to a three-story Dutch colonial in the more
bucolic suburb of Sleepy Hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that living in a relaxed environment -- and perhaps
more importantly being in a wonderful, loving relationship -- has
contributed to a sense of peace, satisfaction and happiness which I
think has allowed me to probe deeper,'' Redman said. ''I have found
a type of balance in my life that I didn't have five years ago when
it was just all about being on the road and playing music.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've learned how to turn opportunities down. ... I reached a
point where I was always in demand to perform, and I feel very
grateful for that, but I realized I couldn't do that all the time.
It was starting to hurt my music and my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Redman says he has ''no regrets'' about his
decision to take a chance on jazz rather than follow the safer path
to law school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, I would love to be able to do everything that interests
me, but I'm very happy with the choices that I've made,'' Redman
said. ''I just feel so lucky to be able to play the music that I
love and make a living at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
