<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Ronnie Milsap  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- There's a bit of resignation in Ronnie
Milsap's voice, but the stronger emotion is determination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Folks say you need a record that anybody 20 years old can
catch on to, just like that,'' Milsap said, snapping his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap, who scored hits throughout the '70s and '80s, quit
releasing new music five years ago. Now that he's back, Milsap
knows he needs to connect with an audience that grew younger while
he was away.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all part of what you can market,'' the 54-year-old Milsap
said. ''The whole thing -- as always -- is being able to sell
records.''
</P>
<P>
   He has just re-released his old hits on the double CD ''40 1
Hits'' (Virgin Records). Two new songs on the collection represent
his first attempt at radio play in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In a review of one of the singles, ''Time, Love and Money,'' for
trade magazine Music Row, critic Robert K. Oermann wrote: ''Turn it
up! This radical reworking of a legend brings out the passion that
has always lurked just beneath his surface. If Kenny (Rogers) can
come back to No. 1, so should Ronnie on this slammer with a
message.''
</P>
<P>
   ''40 1 Hits'' is a good reminder of the impressive track record
the blind piano player from the Great Smoky Mountains of North
Carolina has built over 25 years, including perennial radio
favorites ''Almost Like a Song'' and ''I Wouldn't Have Missed It
for the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Nashville president Scott Hendricks, who has produced
Faith Hill and Brooks &AMP; Dunn, is helping Milsap modernize.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'I'm going to take you into the 21st century if I
have to take you dragging and clawing and screaming,''' Milsap said
with a laugh. ''He understands today's music probably better than I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Milsap was born near Robbinsville, N.C. He has been blind since
birth due to congenital glaucoma. When he was 6, he was enrolled at
the Governor Morehead School for the Blind in Raleigh. The school
taught classical music, and Milsap learned violin and piano.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he led a rock group called The Apparitions. Then
he moved on to a junior college in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ''In college, I was the only blind person there,'' he said.
''But I could sit around this room where a piano was ... all day
and take requests and sing for people. And it meant something.''
</P>
<P>
   He scored an R&AMP;B hit in 1965, ''Never Had It So Good.'' He moved
from Atlanta to Memphis and became a popular club performer and
recording session pianist for producer Chips Moman.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, Milsap played on records by Petula Clark,
Dionne Warwick and Elvis Presley. He can be heard singing at the
end of Presley's hit ''Kentucky Rain,'' hitting some high notes
that were out of the king's vocal range. Presley would book Milsap
as the entertainment for his private parties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Milsap got a job at the King of the Road Motor Inn in
Nashville, and found himself the entertainer that other
entertainers came to see.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was somebody famous up there with me every night,'' he
said. He jammed with Charlie Rich, Faron Young, Mac Davis and most
other stars of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap signed with RCA records in 1973. He scored his first No.
1 hit with ''Pure Love,'' written by ''Kentucky Rain'' songwriter
Eddie Rabbitt.
</P>
<P>
   His first six albums were straight-ahead country, though Milsap
was always different because he played piano and had an R&AMP;B lilt to
his vocals. He crossed over to the pop charts with ''It Was Almost
Like a Song'' in 1977. His other crossover hits included ''I
Wouldn't Have Missed It for the World'' and ''Any Day Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Crossover was such a despised word back then,'' said Milsap.
''I was chastised for just a guitar solo on 'Stranger in My House'
for being too rock.''
</P>
<P>
   A switch to the Liberty label in 1993 was unsuccessful. In 1995,
he began performing at a theater named for him in Myrtle Beach,
S.C. He returned to Nashville three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I wanted to be in the studio trying to get stuff on the
radio,'' Milsap said. ''Every blind guy loves the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Virgin Records in Nashville is:
http://www.virginrecordsnashville.com
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Milsap has a site under construction at
http://www.ronniemilsap.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
