<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of June
18-24:
<TEXT>
<P>
   70 years ago: Wallace Beery starred in ''The Big House,''
directed by George Hill.
</P>
<P>
   55 years ago: ''The Naughty Nineties'' film, directed by Jean
Yarbrough, was notable for Abbott and Costello's legendary ''Who's
on First?'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   45 years ago: David Lean's ''Summertime,'' starring Katharine
Hepburn and Rossano Brazzi, premiered in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And Walt Disney's ''Lady and the Tramp'' was released. It was
the Disney studio's first feature cartoon in CinemaScope.
</P>
<P>
   40 years ago: Vincent Price starred in Roger Corman's ''House of
Usher.'' It was the first of Corman's eight film adaptations of
classic tales by Edgar Allan Poe.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: John Lennon's second book, ''A Spaniard in the
Works,'' was published in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra and Trevor Howard starred in ''Von Ryan's
Express.''
</P>
<P>
   And John Wayne and Dean Martin starred in ''The Sons of Katie
Elder.''
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: Mae West and Raquel Welch starred in ''Myra
Breckenridge.''
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: Steven Spielberg's ''Jaws'' opened in theaters
across the country. The film starred Roy Scheider, Robert Shaw and
Richard Dreyfuss.
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: Donna Summer became the first act signed by David
Geffen to his new Geffen record label.
</P>
<P>
   And ''The Blues Brothers'' starred John Belushi and Dan Aykroyd.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Don Ameche, Wilford Brimley, Hume Cronyn and
Jessica Tandy starred in ''Cocoon,'' directed by Ron Howard. Ameche
won an Oscar for his performance.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Billy Joel was the first rock artist to perform at
New York's Yankee Stadium. He played before two sellout crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Gary Busey paid $242,000 for one of Buddy Holly's guitars
at an auction in New York City. Busey played Holly in a film
biography.
</P>
<P>
   And singer Little Richard was honored with a star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: ''Batman Forever'' sold $52.8 million in tickets
as it rode a wave of hype ranging from sneak previews to
hamburgers. The third ''Batman'' film, starring Val Kilmer, Jim
Carrey and Nicole Kidman, broke the weekend opening record of $50.2
million set by ''Jurassic Park'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And before his new album was even released, Michael Jackson
apologized for anti-Jewish slurs, saying he had intended to make a
statement against prejudice. Instead, he raised the suspicion he
was trying to exploit anger as a publicity stunt. ''They Don't Care
About Us,'' one of the songs on Jackson's ''HIStory: Past, Present
and Future, Book 1,'' featured Jackson swearing and using the
phrases ''Jew me'' and ''kike me.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: Eric Clapton's beloved Fender guitar he called
''Brownie'' went for a record $497,500 at a charity auction in New
York City. It was one of 100 guitars that Clapton offered for sale.
In all, the sale generated $5 million for a Caribbean drug and
alcohol clinic founded by the rocker in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken five years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I've done an absurdly commercial cartoon, and now I'm more
likely to get a job I couldn't get hired for before because I
hadn't done enough movies.'' -- Val Kilmer, star of ''Batman
Forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
