<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Jails Gunman Freed by Italy  </HEADLINE>
By LOUIS MEIXLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- The gunman who shot Pope John Paul II was
locked in a solitary confinement cell in the Turkish prison that he
once escaped from, and Wednesday began serving the rest of a
10-year sentence for assassinating a newspaper editor.
</P>
<P>
   Italy pardoned Mehmet Ali Agca on Tuesday after he served almost
20 years in prison for the 1981 attempted assassination of the pope
in St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   Agca, who is believed to have had links with Turkish right-wing
extremists, has to serve the remaining nine years and seven months
of his sentence for shooting Abdi Ipekci, a liberal newspaper
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Agca's return has raised hopes that the gunman will be able to
shed light on the killing of Ipekci, who had written critical
columns on nationalists and was investigating the actions of
Turkish criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
   There have been allegations that Agca killed Ipekci on the
instructions of gangs that may have had ties to the state and that
he was aided in his escape from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit welcomed Agca's extradition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lifting of a secret curtain over the Abdi Ipekci murder
could shed light on the dark pages of recent history,'' Ecevit
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Agca is to appear in an Istanbul courtroom to be
arraigned in the 1979 robbery of a soft drink factory as well as
the theft of a car that he allegedly used to escape from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Kenan Altmisdort said Agca was also wanted for the
robbery of a jewelry shop, but that Turkey may need Italy's
permission to prosecute Agca on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   According to an extradition agreement with Italy, Turkey will
not retry Agca in the Ipekci case and will seek Italy's permission
if Agca is tried in new cases other than that involving the
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Agca was put in solitary confinement in Kartal prison -- the same
prison he escaped from in 1979. It was not clear how long he will
be kept in solitary.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities increased security at the prison, boosting the
number of searches on visitors and slashing the time that visitors
could see prisoners from a half hour to 10 minutes, the Anatolia
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Agca will serve his 10-year sentence for the 1979 assassination
of Ipekci, minus the 158 days that he was in prison in Turkey
before escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his pardon in Italy, many questions remain about Agca's
role in both shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Agca at first said that he acted alone in shooting the pope, but
later said the Bulgarian secret service and the KGB were behind the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Agca confessed to killing Ipekci but later retracted
his statements. Ipekci was shot nine times by two gunmen; Agca was
convicted for the shooting; the second gunman remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   A Turkish court sentenced Agca to death in absentia a year after
his escape. A 1991 amnesty reduced the sentence to 10 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, a Turkish soldier said ultra-nationalists paid
him to provide Agca with a military uniform and sneak him out of
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Many ultra-nationalists regard Agca as a hero for having killed
Ipekci.
</P>
<P>
   Sevket Can Ozbay, a lawyer who represented the families of slain
soldiers during the trial of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan,
made a request to the Justice Ministry on Wednesday to represent
Agca, NTV television reported.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if his request would be accepted. Ozbay faces
disciplinary action by the Ankara Bar Association for attending the
Ocalan hearings either wearing a T-shirt emblazoned with the
blood-red Turkish flag or draping the Turkish flag around his
shoulders like a cape.
</P>
<P>
   Ozbay said he has known Agca for 25 years, NTV reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1454 </TRAILER>
