<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 70; Nasdaq Down 14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher Wednesday after the
government's most closely watched inflation gauge rose less than
expected, raising investors' hopes that the economy is growing at a
pace moderate enough to satisfy the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But trading was fairly choppy as investors moved cautiously,
reallocating money from technology stocks to industrial names that
have been neglected in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 70.31 at 10,692.19.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 4.38 at 1,473.82, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 14.45 at 3,836.61.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said the Consumer Price
Index inched up 0.1 percent in May. Many analysts had expected an
increase of 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which showed costs for gasoline, tobacco and
clothing falling, raised hopes that inflation is now under control
and the Fed will be willing to leave interest rates unchanged at
its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''Coming on the heels of the recent spate of weaker economic
reports, the better than expected inflation news will probably
cause the Fed to leave interest rates unchanged,'' said Mark
Vitner, economist at First Union Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Six rate increases in the past year have resulted in some modest
signs of a slowdown, allowing investors to look forward to a ''soft
landing,'' in which the economy slows down without grinding to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose $2.688 to $70.563. On Tuesday, the company
appealed a federal judge's decision to split the company in two.
Microsoft is fighting to have the appeal heard by the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, which has been sympathetic in the past.
Meanwhile, the Department of Justice is gunning to have the case
moved directly to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, technology stocks lagged behind the broad market.
Qualcomm fell $7.813 to $73.813 and Oracle fell $2.063 to $79.625.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line industrial stocks were helping the Dow's advance. Alcoa
rose $1.938 to $30.125 and Honeywell rose $1.25 to $51.438.
Analysts said many investors who have been encouraged by the recent
slate of benign economic reports are seeking out these names
because they appear undervalued relative to technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram shot up $7.25 to $60.25 after confirming that it is in
merger talks with French conglomerate Vivendi SA and its
pay-television unit Canal Plus. The Wall Street Journal said the
deal would value Seagram at about $75 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks were mostly higher. Crude oil prices are hovering
near their highest levels in three months amid speculation earlier
this week that OPEC will not increase oil production. Exxon Mobil
rose $2.063 to $83.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 725.78 million
shares, compared with 717.06 million at the same time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.38 to 515.13.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
