<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier Dealt Legal Blow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's Supreme Court on Wednesday dealt a
legal blow to an Israeli soldier's fight against extradition to
Canada on murder charges, saying Israel need not request additional
evidence that the soldier said proved his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   A district court ruled last month that Daniel Weiz, 19, can be
extradited to Canada to face second-degree murder charges in the
November killing of Dimitri Baranovski, 15, in a Toronto park
during a scuffle over money and a pack of cigarettes. Two other
teens in Canada are in custody facing similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   Weiz petitioned the Supreme Court to order Israel's attorney
general to request affidavits given in Canada by teen-agers who
were at the park but said they did not see Weiz participate in the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel said that additional evidence from Canada
would not affect the lower court's ruling that the affidavits it
did consider -- from three teens who said they saw Weiz beat
Baranovski -- constituted grounds for extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Weiz, who lives with his mother in Israel, was visiting his
father in Toronto at the time of the killing. He has admitted to
being in the park but denies kicking and stomping Baranovski to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israeli law, an Israeli citizen can be extradited to stand
trial in another country but has the option of serving the sentence
in Israel if convicted. Weiz holds Canadian residency, and Canada
has promised to return him to Israel to serve any time in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
