<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Will Bashar Press on With Crusade?  </HEADLINE>
By HAMZA HENDAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- From the second floor of his home, former
Prime Minister Mahmoud el-Zoubi could hear the conversation below
between members of his family and an unexpected visitor carrying a
court summons. The talk halted abruptly when a gunshot rang out.
</P>
<P>
   El-Zoubi had chosen to end his life rather than answer
corruption charges, knowing his inquisitors enjoyed the backing of
Bashar Assad, the son of President Hafez Assad and the head of an
anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With his father's death Saturday, the 34-year-old son and chosen
heir must decide if he should carry on with the campaign. While it
won him praise and support from ordinary Syrians, it now means
risking alienating powerful figures whose backing he may need to
consolidate power.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption in Syria pervades all levels of society, including
the ruling Baath Party and the political establishment set up by
Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ''Corruption has become so entrenched that it has reached the
point where people brag about their corruption,'' said George
Jabbour, a former adviser to Hafez Assad. ''The civil servant who
does not accept bribes is now a fool and the clean politician is an
ass.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Zoubi, who killed himself with a single shot to the head on
May 21, was prime minister for 13 years before he was forced to
resign in March. The Damascus city police commander, who had come
to deliver the summons, rushed el-Zoubi to a hospital where he was
declared dead on arrival.
</P>
<P>
   El-Zoubi's deputy for economic affairs, Salim Yassin, and his
transport minister, Mofeid Abdul-Kareem, are under investigation,
also on corruption charges. Several directors at various ministries
have been sacked as part of Bashar's drive to root out corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hikmat Al-Shihabi, Syria's chief-of-staff for 20 years
until 1998, fled to the United States this month to join a son in
California. According to a London-based Arabic newspaper, he felt
his turn might be next. Unconfirmed reports circulating in Damascus
speak of millions of dollars illegally earned from arms deals.
</P>
<P>
   While Assad was alive, Bashar had a free hand in going after the
corrupt. But if he is to continue, Bashar could upset the delicate
balance of power that his father maintained between the majority
Sunni Muslims and the minority Alawite sect to which the Assad
family belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad gave Alawites, who are an offshoot of the Shiite
sect, control of powerful positions in the army and the Baath party
while the Sunnis were given a free rein to get rich on trade and
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The formula was severely tested at times during Hafez Assad's
rule, but has on the whole miraculously lasted. Bashar may not want
to put it to another test in his early days at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe that Bashar will put on hold his
anti-corruption campaign, even if temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ''He now has balances to consider and must pay attention to
delicate considerations.'' said Imad Fawzi Shueibi, a political
sociology lecturer at the University of Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   An indication that Bashar would follow the footsteps of his
father came in an editorial in the government newspaper, Tishrin,
which reflects the official view.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians bidding farewell to Assad expressed their loyalty to his
''struggle and his unshakable ... positions in defending the
homeland and not conceding an iota of territory or a single
right.'' They reassured the late leader of support for his son, who
''has made public his determination to complete the immortal
mission (of his father) and the march toward construction and
liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for Bashar, however, may come from the ordinary people
who realize that a clean administration could give them a better
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''Assad is in heaven and Bashar is our hope,'' was one of the
more popular slogans chanted by ordinary Syrians during mourning
processions for Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's conflict with Israel and its military involvement in
Lebanon since 1976 have sapped its limited resources. Reforms in
the state-dominated planned economy have been painfully slow.
</P>
<P>
   But was Bashar's campaign really about corruption?
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that it was in reality a purge inspired by
Assad to get rid of likely opponents to his succession. In a
country where the media is under tight state control and
information is nearly impossible to come by, it may take years for
the truth to be known.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, Bashar will most likely put the campaign on ice
until he strengthens his hold on power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1538 </TRAILER>
