<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Songwriters Trying To Get Noticed  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Songwriters' Hall of Fame has been sleepy,
rudderless and homeless for much of its 31 years. Talk about an
identity problem: Its former chairman, Frank Sinatra, was a great
interpreter of songs but didn't write any.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under the direction of veteran songwriter Hal David, the
New York-based organization is making a big bid for attention.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, it will honor some of the biggest names in
music -- Brian Wilson, James Taylor, Curtis Mayfield, Neil Diamond,
James Brown, Don Henley and Glenn Frey -- at a ceremony in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the years I've regretted watching the way the music
business has gone to where the artist, the performing artist, is
the focus of attention,'' said David, author of ''Raindrops Keep
Falling on My Head,'' ''Close to You'' and ''I'll Never Fall in
Love Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When people hear a song, they think of Frank Sinatra or
Madonna, whoever it might be, even if the artist didn't write the
song,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's induction ceremony is a dry run for what organizers
hope becomes an annual televised event that stands with such yearly
music moments as the Grammy Awards, Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
induction ceremony and MTV Video Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Krantz, a partner in the John Schreiber Group, a television
production team, was organizing Thursday's ceremony to make it
TV-friendly. If all goes well, he hopes a TV deal for future years
is in place by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   David was installed to shake things up at the hall, which was
founded by the late lyricist Johnny Mercer. Sinatra died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   David's big plans include finally getting a physical location
for the Hall of Fame. David said he is close to an agreement with
New York University to build one in a dormitory the college is
building. The hall would have its own entrance.
</P>
<P>
   David won't criticize his organization for failing to lodge
itself in the public consciousness before he took over.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe the timing wasn't right,'' he said. ''The timing is
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Henley and Frey, all of the artists being honored
Thursday and the family of the late Curtis Mayfield plan to be at
the Sheraton Hotel for the ceremony. Henley is on tour; the reason
for Frey's absence is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Carole King will salute Taylor by performing some of his work;
Hanson will do a medley of Wilson's Beach Boys tunes; Brian
McKnight will pay tribute to Mayfield; J.D. Souther will perform
some of Henley and Frey's Eagles songs; and Jill Sobule will sing
Diamond's ''I'm a Believer.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond is already a member of the hall and is getting a
lifetime achievement award Thursday. Organizers are also giving the
Towering Song Award to two tunes: ''You Are My Sunshine'' and ''All
of Me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1539 </TRAILER>
