<DOCNO> APW20000614.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hardship Is Reality for N. Koreans  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Beneath chandeliers, gloved waiters
tend banquet tables laid with linen. Sleek limousines slide past
manicured gardens. Child stage performers prance in opulent
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily controlled television images from Pyongyang this
week during a summit between leaders of North Korea and South Korea
depict a cultural capital, an elegant city studded with monuments.
Yet hardship is the reality of life for most North Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the communist country's 22 million people don't get
enough to eat, don't have electricity in their homes and walk
everywhere because there is no transport. By some estimates, up to
two million people died of famine in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented summit, at which Korea's leaders signed a deal
Wednesday agreeing to work toward reunification, was a chance for
impoverished North Korea to showcase its regal capital. The face it
showed to the world was one of splendor, but the pomp highlighted
the economic divide between the ruling class and the powerless.
</P>
<P>
   The TV footage of parades, state dinners and stage performances
was an example of how tightly North Korea tries to regulate its
image. Fifty South Korean journalists were allowed to accompany
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung on his trip to Pyongyang, while
foreign reporters were barred from traveling there altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean journalists described how North Korean minders
kept a close eye on them, limiting them to filing only pool reports
and banning impromptu interviews with people on the street. Most
television footage of street scenes was filmed from moving
vehicles, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of traffic in Pyongyang is a sign that living
conditions are basic. But the image campaign of North Korean leader
Kim Jong Il has swayed some people in South Korea, who have avidly
watched live television reports from Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've always thought North Koreans were so poor and lived so
differently, but on television, their lives didn't seem so bad,''
said Hwang Hye-yon, a 55-year-old cloth vendor in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ''But perhaps it's a facade they were showing to the world, and
maybe it's different behind that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is far more precarious in rural areas, where
international aid workers say food shortages remain widespread
despite better harvests after several years of low yields caused by
bad weather and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean officials, who have relied heavily on outside food
aid since 1995, have become more candid about the urgency of their
needs. Yet they have controlled the access of most foreign aid
workers, prompting several aid groups to pull out of the isolated
country since last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is done to hide all the interesting things we
should see and know,'' said Jean-Fabrice Pietri of Association
Contre La Faim, a Paris-based aid group that left North Korea in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Pietri said he had to inform North Koreans of field visits one
week in advance. On some occasions, he said, officials said they
could not give him lists of nurseries in an area because they were
''military secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Many villages, especially those in mountainous areas, are
struggling to provide enough food for residents, said Erich
Weingartner, a former employee of the U.N. World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   More street markets are visible as people struggle to make a
living in defiance of socialist edicts forbidding private
enterprise. The government, unable to feed its people, largely
ignores these violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even in some provincial cities, you see a lot of people with a
little table and they might sell just a few items along the side of
the road,'' Weingartner said. Goods include baskets and other
handicrafts, balls of bean paste, furniture, and fruit and
vegetables grown in home gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The images of Pyongyang that have been broadcast back to Seoul
have featured mostly tree-lined avenues and monolithic state
buildings, not the city's cramped neighborhoods with outhouses and
no power.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Byong-joon, a South Korean doctor who traveled to the North
Korean port of Nampo by ship earlier this year to donate a batch of
eggs, said officials there heavily monitored his movements.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said: 'I am a dentist. Let me look around a hospital,''' Kim
said. ''They wanted me to stay in the hotel. I was a little
disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1546 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Monitoring Gusinksy Case  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia's international reputation could be
severely harmed if the government restricts press freedom, State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Tuesday's arrest in Moscow of media tycoon
Vladimir Gusinsky, Boucher said U.S. diplomats have spoken with
Russian authorities and are closely following the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important that Mr. Gusinsky is afforded due process
rights and protections in accordance with the Russian constitution
and law,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there have been a series of recent events in Russia that
have drawn international attention to the issue of press freedom,
including a police raid last month on the headquarters of
Gusinsky's Media-Most holding company.
</P>
<P>
   ''Press freedom is an important issue to us,'' Boucher said.
''The secretary and the president both made that clear in Moscow
during the summit'' earlier this month with Russian President
Vladimir Putin. ''And we're looking very, very very closely at this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States agreed that ''Russia's international
standing will be severely damaged if the government lets stand
actions that are intended to intimidate independent media and
voices with whom it does not agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was arrested Tuesday night and put in Moscow's
Butyrskaya jail. He was being held on suspicion of taking part in
the theft of $10 million in state funds in a privatization deal.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest has been widely viewed as revenge for Media-Most's
criticism of the Putin government and assailed as a step toward
Soviet-style repression of dissent. Media-Most includes NTV
television and several other media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Putin denied Wednesday that Gusinsky'a arrest was punishment for
criticizing the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also said during a two-day visit to Spain that he had not
known about the arrest and promised to look into the case on his
return. If the law were violated, Putin said, he would take action
against those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Interfax news agency, Putin said he did not
''see a political aspect'' in the arrest. ''As for criminal, I
don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Press Club in Washington said the arrest was ''a
very troubling incident.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While the facts are still unclear, there seems to be an
indication that the new Russian leaders under President Vladimir
Putin are moving to shut down a private news organization that has
been critical of the government,'' said Richard A. Ryan, the club's
vice president, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said any efforts to close down or control press freedom ''is
a setback to the advance of democratic reforms in Russia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
