<HEADLINE> Jailed Tycoon Built Media Empire  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Vladimir Gusinsky began his professional life as a
theater director, then moved on to real-life high drama in the
bare-knuckled world of Russian business.
</P>
<P>
   His enterprises included founding Russia's largest independent
media company, and Gusinsky is regarded by many as a prime force in
developing a free press after decades of state-controlled media.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's NTV television station and Segodnya newspaper
frequently have run reports critical of Russia's Chechnya policy
and on alleged high-level corruption. Gusinsky's arrest Tuesday on
charges of swindling and grand larceny are interpreted as a Kremlin
attack on press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old Gusinsky started out as a provincial theater
director in the town of Tula and then organized theater tours in
Siberia in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As economic reforms sprouted in the Soviet Union in the late
1980s, Gusinsky became one of the early entrepreneurs to take
advantage of them. He hustled his way up from small-time,
fast-dollar dealing to become one of the tycoons known as
''oligarchs'' for their influence on national affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Boris Yeltsin consulted him, along with the
other moguls, on key decisions, and NTV coverage helped Yeltsin win
re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the early reform years, Gusinsky first jostled to buy and
sell office furniture and computers, then worked in real estate and
in a consulting venture to advise American businesses on how to
cope with Russia's complicated and often chaotic business climate.
In 1989, he founded the Most commercial bank, which was the first
in Russia to offer customers credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Doing business in Russia at Gusinsky's level of wealth carries
physical risks and like other moguls he relied on large and
well-armed private security company, which has become a source of
friction with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Kremlin security guards raided Most offices and forced
company security guards and employees to lie face down in the snow
at gunpoint. Later, pro-Kremlin media reported that the government
was investigating Gusinsky's staff on allegations of corruption and
abuse of office.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky fled the country for a few months and later said he
feared for his life at this time.
</P>
<P>
   But NTV continued to run piercing reports on the first war in
Chechnya, sometimes reporting from rebel positions, bringing
Russians harsh images of their government's bloody military
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Like other oligarchs, Gusinsky rallied behind Yeltsin during his
1996 campaign to defeat his communist challenger for the
presidency, and later that year won a license to open a private
satellite network. The license was widely seen as a reward for
favorable coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But relations again soured between Gusinsky and the Kremlin as
he resumed critical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   NTV broadcast reports on the influence of rival tycoon Boris
Berezovsky on Yeltsin and his daughter Tatyana Dyachenko and on
official decisions, and continued criticism of Yeltsin's successor
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has said the Kremlin tried to bribe him with millions
of dollars for favorable coverage last summer, but that he refused.
</P>
<P>
   Police raided his companies last month, saying they were
investigating illegal eavesdropping by his security service. A
court later ruled the raid illegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1549 </TRAILER>
