<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disputed Matisse Painting Returned  </HEADLINE>
By ALESSANDRA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Organizers of a touring art exhibit from Russia's
Hermitage Museum abruptly bought a famous Matisse a one-way ticket
back to St. Petersburg, pre-empting what they feared would be a
court-ordered seizure in Italy over its ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Dance'' was supposed to go on display in Milan on June 26,
after being the highlight of a hugely successful six-month exhibit
in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at the Hermitage's request, authorities put the work on
a flight to St. Petersburg on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest turn in an international dispute pitting the
Russian museum against the heirs to the pre-Russian Revolution
industrialist who first collected the painting, Sergei Shtukin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Hermitage's decision speaks for itself,'' Mario Guttieres,
a lawyer for Shtukin's grandson, Andre-Marc Delocque-Fourcaud, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Delocque-Fourcaud asked Italian authorities to
confiscate ''The Dance'' on the grounds he is the rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   Delocque-Fourcaud told France's Le Figaro newspaper the painting
was taken from his family in 1918 after the revolution, along with
450 other pieces his grandfather had collected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that the thief was Lenin himself doesn't justify the
theft,'' Delocque-Fourcaud told Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained of the ''commercial exploitation'' of the
canvas, which became the trademark of the Rome exhibit and was used
on show souvenirs such as wrapping paper, scarves and ashtrays.
</P>
<P>
   A Rome court is expected to rule in July whether international
copyright law was violated, Guttieres said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Dance,'' painted by the French master in 1910, depicts
five bodies dancing in a circle against a blue and green
background.
</P>
<P>
   Shtukin's family has campaigned for years to get it back, along
with the collection's other pieces, which include works by Picasso
and Braque.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when the Matisse painting was in Paris for an exhibit
at the Pompidou Center, Shtukin's daughter Irina, appealed to a
French court but her claim was rejected. She died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government also has rebuffed the family's claim to
the collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1601 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
