<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Church Escalates ID Battle  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   THESSALONIKI, Greece (AP) -- The leader of the Greek Orthodox
Church told followers Wednesday to unite against the government in
an identity card dispute that has set Greece's most powerful
institutions against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a rally of more than 100,000 people, Archbishop
Christodoulos sharply escalated a fight that strikes at the essence
of the Greek identity and whether politicians can govern without
the consent of the Orthodox church hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your efforts are futile,'' cried Christodoulos in an obvious
attack against the long-governing Socialists. ''The people do not
follow you. ... You think you will accomplish you plans with the
sword of power. You are mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown began with government plans to strip the religious
affiliation entry from state ID cards. The government says privacy
laws require the change, which is strongly supported by rights
groups and religious minorities such as Jews and Muslims who claim
the IDs make them targets for discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But the church and many followers see the religious entry as an
important symbol of the historical role of the Orthodox church,
which considers itself the true guardian of Greek identity.
</P>
<P>
   For church leaders, there also is the fear of possible moves
toward a formal separation of church and state in Greece. About 97
percent of the native-born population are baptized into the Greek
Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   The church protests have upset government leaders. Premier
Costas Simitis' government, which is trying to bring Greece into
the mainstream of the European Union, complained the church was
adopting a political character ''not in line with its role,'' said
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament speaker Apostolos Kaklamanis called the rally ''a
mob, not the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I fear the situation in the church could spawn great dangers
for the future of this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crusade also has split the church itself. Some top clerics
have refused to join the protests, saying the ID issue is purely
political. The spiritual head of the Orthodox faith, Patriarch
Bartholomew I, issued a letter to Simitis saying the ID reforms are
the ''jurisdiction of the state,'' the government-run Athens News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police were on full alert around Thessaloniki during Wednesday's
rally, and Christodoulos' 80-minute speech was broadcast live on
Greek news programs.
</P>
<P>
   Another rally is planned for Athens on June 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1603 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0125 </DOCNO>
