<HEADLINE> Treasury Sec'y Urges AIDS Awareness  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN LINNEE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers pulled a crinkled dollar bill out of his pocket Wednesday
and told a gathering of puzzled AIDS orphans and HIV-positive
Tanzanians that his job was to sign bank notes.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain the connection, he told the group that had
gathered at the Wamata AIDS center that his job was to make sure
there is money to do things that make a difference in the battle
against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very real economic and financial issue,'' he said.
''It can stop countries from realizing what they can realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers was in Tanzania on the second stop of a five-nation
African tour to highlight U.S. appeals for international debt
relief and AIDS awareness on the continent. Other stops include
Nigeria, South Africa, Mozambique and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year-old Wamata project, funded by international donors,
aims to provide support and counseling, mostly to HIV-positive
young people. It also carries out AIDS testing and supports orphans
of those who have died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised speech Sunday, Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa warned of the rapid spread of AIDS in this East
African nation of 31 million people and the danger it poses to its
fragile economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Mkapa told listeners he sympathized with those who had lost
loved ones to AIDS because he himself had lost relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, there were three known cases of AIDS in Tanzania; in
1998 there were 600,000, with one in 10 Tanzanians HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of AIDS victims and HIV-infected Tanzanians is
probably much higher, Mkapa said, adding that the statistics were
based on those who were being treated in hospitals or health
centers, or who had been tested for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Summers announced a $25,000 grant to the Wamata center ''to
support people like you who speak out about the disease.'' The
United States is providing $7 million to Tanzania to deal with
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration wants to make the fight against AIDS
in Africa and providing debt relief for the world's poorest nations
top priorities during the so-called Group of Eight summit next
month in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Debt relief will come, and it will come as soon as it is clear
that debt relief is going to efforts like this,'' Summers said,
just before signing a dollar bill ''to the good people of the
Wamata health clinic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
