<HEADLINE> Rain Floods Central, Southern Chile  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Streets in the capital were turned to
rivers Wednesday and thousands were forced to flee their homes
after days of heavy rains forced the government to declare a state
of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The rains, which began Monday, were the worst in 20 years,
affecting and a large portion of central and southern Chile, said
Interior Minister Jose Miguel Insulza.
</P>
<P>
   Some 75 percent of the streets in the capital were submerged.
</P>
<P>
   The Mapocho River, which crosses through the capital, overflowed
its banks, flooding fields on the outskirts of the city. Many
routes into the capital were closed because of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ''Santiago is clearly not prepared for this kind of rain,''
President Ricardo Lagos said Wednesday as he surveyed the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The neighboring port city of Valparaiso was also hit by the
flooding, and landslides were reported outside town. Both cities
were declared disaster zones.
</P>
<P>
   Activity in the capital ground to a halt, as classes were
suspended and government employees were authorized to stay home.
Some subways were shut.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people were forced to leave their homes, especially
in working class neighborhoods and the slums. Many more have been
left homeless because of flooding in the interior of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The weather bureau said about six inches of rain has fallen
since Monday. Rain is expected to decrease gradually and stop
Thursday, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
