<HEADLINE> Fire Knocks Out State Dept. Phones  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fire, apparently caused by an electrical
short, knocked out phone service in parts of the State Department
on Wednesday and forced workers on two floors to evacuate the
building after they locked up classified material.
</P>
<P>
   The fire flared in a basement room near the 21st Street side of
the building. Batteries that power some telephones were put out of
commission, Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was confined to the basement and the damage did not
appear to be widespread, he said. While fire engines responded,
scores of evacuated waited outside for more than an hour until the
fire was extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department spokesman Geoffrey Grambo said a cable that
leads into a voltage room shorted, melting five large storage
batteries used as a back up power source at the building.
</P>
<P>
   Grambo says firefighters used sacks of concrete to prevent
battery acid from spreading inside of the building. Workers and
visitors had to be evacuated because of smoky conditions on the
building's upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   Grambo says there were no reported injuries.
</P>
