<HEADLINE> Rebels Attack Sierra Leone Village  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Rebels attacked and burned a
village near a U.N. peacekeeping outpost Wednesday as civilians
fled rebel-held central Sierra Leone, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether there were any casualties in the attack
on the settlement several miles north of Jordanian U.N. troops
stationed at Rockel Bridge, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge, some 40 miles east of Freetown, the capital, is on
the outer edge of a horseshoe-shaped security cordon maintained by
U.N. troops around the city. On Tuesday, rebels and Jordanian
soldiers exchanged gunfire near the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels also attacked the town of Lunsar, some 55 miles east of
Freetown, overnight for the third time since Monday, government
soldiers said. The report could not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The town, which has been completely abandoned by civilians, has
changed hands several times since the Revolutionary United Front
rebels reignited Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war in early May,
prompting a flood of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said 45,000 people have fled over the past week to the
crossroads town of Mile 91 from the rebel-held central towns of
Magburaka and Makeni. Aid workers says a government helicopter
gunship has dropped bombs on the rebel-held towns in recent days.
The gunship also reportedly has dropped leaflets urging rebels to
surrender their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a 1,000-strong British force that has spent more than
five weeks guarding the capital against a possible rebel attack was
pulling out Wednesday in helicopters and planes. A few remaining
troops were due to leave Thursday, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers were taking over from the British troops. The
United Nations has nearly doubled the strength of the force in
recent weeks, from 6,000 to 11,850 troops, in a bid to help
maintain security in the war-ravaged West African country.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a 200-person British military training team,
including about 150 troops charged with providing security to the
trainers, was staying behind to begin equipping and training 1,000
Sierra Leonean soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have killed tens of thousands of people and mutilated
and raped many others in a campaign to topple Sierra Leone's
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1712 </TRAILER>
