<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census May Get Authority Over Data  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying it would remove partisan influences
from a politically sensitive decision, Commerce Secretary William
Daley proposed Wednesday to give the head of the Census Bureau the
final word over whether to release sampled population data from
this year's count.
</P>
<P>
   The statistically adjusted results could dramatically affect
congressional and state legislative redistricting next year. The
authority to release that data currently lies with the commerce
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Republicans oppose sampling, while Census director
Kenneth Prewitt favors it. Supporters of sampling believe it could
account for portions of the population missed in previous counts,
including minorities and inner-city residents who vote Democrat,
and Prewitt has said it is virtually impossible to find every
person in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department oversees the Census Bureau. Both Prewitt
and Daley were appointed by President Clinton, but each may not be
in their positions by early next year, when the decision to release
sampled data must be made.
</P>
<P>
   If left up to him, Prewitt said his choice will be based purely
on what is best to do scientifically, not politically.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure that when this important decision is
made, it is made by the experts based on sound, statistical
science,'' Daley said in a statement. ''Politics shouldn't play any
part in this decision, and this regulation is a way to ensure that
it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Walker, spokesman for Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of
the House Government Reform Committee's census panel, called the
proposal ''politics as usual.'' He proposed that an independent,
third-party panel play a role in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision just moved from the hands of one political
appointee to another,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Another committee member, Rep. Paul Ryan, R-Wis., called it a
''victory over partisan politics,'' since Prewitt has said the
sampled data would not be ready before Jan. 20 -- the day the next
president takes office.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can continue to debate the merits of sampling over actual
enumeration. Prewitt is a political appointee, but in charge of a
largely scientific agency. I believe he has more credibility in
this arena,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said 99 percent, or 119 million, of the country's 120
million households had participated so far in Census 2000 either by
mail or at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   At-home visits for the Accuracy and Coverage Evaluation of
315,000 households, which sampled data will be based on, begins
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Supreme Court ruled that reapportionment of
congressional seats must be made using raw, or nonsampled data. It
left open the possibility for states to use sampled data when
redrawing state and congressional district boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsampled data is due to President Clinton by Dec. 31. If
approved, sampled data would be released by next April.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, in general, fear sampled data could skew those
political boundaries to Democrats' favor.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the courts, though, that ultimately decide the
legitimacy of sampling. Virginia is suing the Justice Department,
which enforces voting rights regulations, for the right to use
nonsampled data for redistricting without first getting federal
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal could become a formal regulation by September,
following a public comment period, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Census Bureau Web site: http://www.census.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
