<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes GOP's Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in two days, President
Clinton criticized Republican plans to provide prescription drugs
benefits to senior citizens. Still, he offered what he said was an
''olive branch'' in reaching a bipartisan solution this year.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Republicans, who want to rely on private
insurance companies, are opposed to his idea of providing drug
benefits directly through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at a White House event Wednesday to promote his plan,
Clinton said that as long as all senior citizens have the option of
getting prescription drug benefits at an affordable price through
Medicare, he is willing to consider giving them other
private-sector choices as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to offer another olive branch. If they want to offer a
number of options to people, and one of those options is ... a true
Medicare program that is available at the same price to all
seniors, then we could talk,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less, Clinton said, would be ''an empty promise.''
</P>
<P>
   He appeared with Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle, D-S.D.,
and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and
representatives from senior citizen groups.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee could take action on the
Republican plan as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said the Clinton
administration is misrepresenting the Republican plan, which is
supported by some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am perplexed by the president's partisan attack on
congressional efforts to provide a prescription drug benefit to all
Medicare beneficiaries,'' Hastert said. ''Partisanship is the wrong
prescription when it comes to this vital issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., is the chief architect of the
Republican proposal that would enlist private insurers to contract
with Medicare to provide the drug benefits. Thomas said the
government would act as the ''insurer of last resort'' if private
plans failed to offer adequate coverage options everywhere across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says it is not acceptable if the
Republican plan offers this ''last resort'' option only to senior
citizens with few, if any, private options to chose from. Also,
Clinton said, those private choices might not be affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's be clear,'' Clinton said. ''A private insurance model
simply cannot guarantee affordable coverage for all. To make the
promise of affordable coverage real for all older Americans, there
must be a true Medicare drug option.''
</P>
<P>
   At a White House event Tuesday with Democratic lawmakers from
rural areas, which often are overlooked by private insurance
companies, Clinton said the Republican plan ''claims to help
everybody but is a false hope for most.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry has questioned whether the private sector
could offer affordable stand-alone prescription drug policies to
all senior citizens, whose medicine costs are typically high.
</P>
<P>
   ''The evidence suggests that it would be extremely difficult to
ensure the universal availability of drug coverage to seniors
through this type of proposal,'' said Chip Kahn, president of the
Health Insurance Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Health Care Financing Administration:
http://hcfa.hhs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 1811 </TRAILER>
