<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: Korea Summit Won't Affect ABMs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's deliberations on
whether to deploy a national missile defense will not be influenced
by the tension-easing summit between North and South Korea, the
State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think there is a threat to the United States that will come
up in coming years. And we need to be able to deal with that,''
said spokesman Richard Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   A missile defense system would be aimed at protecting the United
States against what U.S. officials consider ''rogue states,'' such
as North Korea, Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said that because other states, as well as terrorists,
also pose a threat, the success of the Korean summit is unlikely to
influence U.S. debate over whether to build a national missile
defense system. Proponents have pointed to the threat from North
Korea as a major justification for deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher noted that North Korea made a commitment last year not
to test an upgraded long-range missile in its possession and said
he hoped this would continue.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ''I don't think we see in (the summit) the seeds
of anything that would change the possibility of a missile threat
to the United States that we would have to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
