<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Approves Action Against Myanmar  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- A U.N. labor organization on Wednesday approved
measures against Myanmar in response to widespread use of forced
labor, but gave the country four months to prove its willingness to
change.
</P>
<P>
   In a 257-41 vote with 31 abstentions, International Labor
Organization delegates agreed to invoke a special article in ILO
rules against Myanmar, also known as Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution recommends that ILO members -- governments,
workers and employers -- ''review their links with Myanmar and take
appropriate measures'' to ensure the country cannot use the links
to extend its system of forced labor. It also refers the issue to a
high-level U.N. committee and agrees it will be discussed at every
future ILO conference until Myanmar is shown to have stopped using
forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   Several Asian nations opposed the measure. Myanmar denounced it
as ''most unfair, most unreasonable and most unjust,'' and Japan,
China, Malaysia, India and other nations spoke out against it.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise, the resolution put off action until the ILO
governing body meets in November to review whether Myanmar is
making serious efforts to stamp out forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis Herman welcomed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ILO and the world community have sent a loud and clear
message that we will no longer tolerate horrific forms of forced
labor,'' she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Myanmar Ambassador Than Mya insisted his country was the
victim of an ''arbitrary judgment based on misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the ILO barred Myanmar from receiving assistance
after a commission reported on the widespread use of forced labor
for infrastructure projects in the country. Myanmar claimed workers
offered their labor freely for the development of the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
