<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- For Steve Stricker, the U.S. Open is
a family affair.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker arrived at Pebble Beach along with his brother-in-law,
Mario Tiziani, who qualified for his first Open by winning a
sectional last week at Boone Valley Golf Club in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm on his tail pretty much everywhere I go,'' Tiziani said
Wednesday. ''Basically, he's taken me by the hand and led me
around. When he putts, I putt. When he hits balls, I hit balls. I'm
like a fish out of water, and he definitely knows his way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker will be playing in his sixth straight Open and seventh
overall. He has finished fifth the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''His goals are a little different than mine,'' said Tiziani,
whose sister, Nicki, is married to Stricker. ''But I think being
here with him is good for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiziani, 29, has been playing on the Buy.com and Canadian tours.
But his most unusual moment came at a Hooters tournament in 1996,
when he finished with a hole-in-one on 17 and a double-eagle on 18
-- and still missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Dennis Tiziani, doubles as the golf coach at
Wisconsin and Stricker's swing instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DALY'S CADDIE: If John Daly makes a long putt, his caddie
might be prone to say, ''He shoots, he scores!''
</P>
<P>
   Former NHL player Dan Quinn is carrying the bag for Daly at the
U.S. Open, taking over after his regular caddie, Ron McCann,
injured an ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who played with the Pittsburgh Penguins and several other
NHL teams, got a call from Daly two days after shooting a record
score to win the Mario Lemieux Celebrity Invitational by 14 shots.
The two became friends several years ago at a charity event in
Erie, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is unbelievable,'' said Quinn, who is at Pebble Beach for
the first time. ''It's a chance of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, 35, will try to qualify for the PGA Tour this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AILING SUTTON: This is not how Hal Sutton wanted to prepare
for the U.S. Open -- spending more time in the fitness trailer than
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, who played last month despite a sore Achilles' tendon,
was warming up on the range Tuesday morning when he felt a twinge
in his back.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to play one hole and decided not to risk further
damage. He was treated for a lower back sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hurt pretty bad,'' he said. ''And I thought, rather than
push this ... I felt like I changed my golf swing trying to do
that. So I decided to get it worked on.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, he said he was feeling better and said he should
be OK for the first round on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to try to beat age,'' he said with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe practice is overrated, anyway. In March, Sutton managed to
get in only nine holes of practice before The Players Championship.
Then, he went out and held off Tiger Woods on the TPC at Sawgrass
to win by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   WATCH THE DEER: A pair of deer weren't the least bit concerned
about getting in the line of fire at the Pebble Beach driving
range.
</P>
<P>
   The animals meandered around the range Wednesday, munching on
grass while dozens of balls fell around them. Occasionally, they
would scoot into the nearby woods when the ball picker got a little
close, only to wander back out when things quieted down.
</P>
<P>
   ''That just shows you how much brains they have,'' Fred Funk
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the deer have enough sense to stay away from the
target flags, restricting their diet to less-dangerous ground.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DIVOTS: Duffy Waldorf stopped by the driving range wearing a
T-shirt and gym shorts. Going to hit a few, Duffy? ''I don't think
that would be too smart in this outfit,'' he replied. Then he
headed back to the PGA's mobile fitness trailer, parked nearby. ...
Mark O'Meara hasn't won since capturing a pair of majors, the
Masters and British Open, in 1998. This year, he has missed the cut
four times and hasn't finished higher than a tie for ninth at The
Players Championship. ''It's been frustrating,'' he said. ''But
it's coming.'' ... California artist Thomas Kinkade set up his
easel alongside the 18th fairway, working on a painting that is
expected to be finished by Thursday and made into a lithograph to
sell. Proceeds will be donated to the Payne Stewart Foundation.
Kinkade plays golf but won't give his handicap. ''People will ask
me what I shoot, and I answer 70,'' he said. ''I don't tell them
it's only for nine holes.''
</P>
