<HEADLINE> Johnson No. 1 at Bills' Mini-Camp  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Rob Johnson has come to the Buffalo
Bills minicamp calm, cool and focused, having reclaimed the title
of No. 1 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson even was spotted sharing a couple of laughs with fellow
quarterback -- and sometime nemesis -- Doug Flutie during practice
Wednesday at Orchard Park Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always been pretty relaxed. I don't worry about that. If
I take care of myself and play well, I won't come out of the game
unless I get hurt,'' Johnson said. ''And if I don't play well, then
I shouldn't be in there anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid the sour Buffalo memories of the Tennessee Titans'
''Music City Miracle'' was the role Johnson played in that AFC
playoff game in January.
</P>
<P>
   The game was only Johnson's second start of the season; Flutie
had been the starter through the team's first 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   On the Bills' final possession, Johnson drove the Bills 38 yards
on six plays to set up Steve Christie's go-ahead 41-yard field goal
with 16 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That, as far as Johnson is concerned, still means something.
</P>
<P>
   ''We left the field and thought we had won,'' Johnson said.
''For me it was nice. It was the last drive of the game, and it
felt like we won a playoff game on the road against the best team
in the AFC.''
</P>
<P>
   At 27, Johnson wants to show he can play like that on a
consistent basis. Acquired from Jacksonville in 1998 for two draft
picks, including a first-rounder, Johnson's tenure with the Bills
has been beset by bad luck and injuries -- he lost the starting job
to a rib injury five games into the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a jammed finger on his left, non-throwing hand,
Johnson is healthy now.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Eric Moulds likes what he has seen in Johnson the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks pretty sharp. He's coming in and knows what to expect
and what it takes to be a starting quarterback in this league,''
Moulds said. ''In that position, he has to be one of the leaders on
the team. He knows his position, I think he'll handle it well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
