<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness pleads for mercy for convicted killer in boy witness case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - The grandmother of three of Russell
Peeler's children described him as a warm, loving father as she
pleaded for his life to a jury that will decide whether he gets the
death penalty in the murders of an 8-year-old boy and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In rambling testimony filled with asides to the jury, Mary Bush
said she does not believe Peeler arranged the killings of Leroy
''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke. The same jury
convicted Peeler in the killings last week, finding that Peeler
ordered his brother, Adrian, to commit the murders to prevent B.J.
from testifying against him in an earlier murder case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wouldn't go as far as to be the monster they're trying to
create,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That boy there is not the one,'' she said. ''Russell is not no
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was called by the defense on the second day of a hearing to
decide Peeler's punishment. He will receive either life in prison
without the possibility of release or death.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pleaded with the jury to spare Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is somebody's life. This is somebody's mother's child,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the jury that Peeler, now 28, had three children with
her daughter, Angelina Keene.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Peeler taught his oldest daughter, Russell, 9, to use
a computer and ''set a good example for her.'' He also has
3-year-old twins, Sheila and Russell, named after his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''He loves his children very much,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan
Benedict told Bush that the state had an enforcement action against
Peeler for $20,000 in unpaid child support. He also asked Bush if
she was familiar with ''The Bush Mob,'' a drug gang started by
members of her family.
</P>
<P>
   She described it as ''a bunch of kids,'' but Benedict said one
of the group's leaders was now serving a prison sentence for
murder.
</P>
<P>
   As she stepped down from the witness stand, Bush muttered to the
jury, ''Be careful. That's all I got to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's brother, Oswald Clarke, said outside court that he was
upset that Bush focused on Peeler's children in seeking mercy from
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''His children? What about B.J.?'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also called the controversial host of a local cable
show to testify on Peeler's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry ''Jer'' McClellan said he was a close friend of Peeler
when the two were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan described Peeler as a ''jokester'' and ''class
clown.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was never violent - never got into any fights that I know
of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Peeler seemed to change after his mother died of
cancer in 1993 when he was 21.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think when his mother died, it took a lot out of him,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Joseph Corradino asked McClellan if
he had been convicted on drug charges in 1993. McClellan
acknowledged the conviction, but said he had turned his life
around.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan's local access show was pulled off the air in 1996 by
Cablevision of Connecticut after several viewers complained about
the appearance of a topless stripper. McClellan, who sometimes wore
a sanitary napkin on his head while performing, had argued that
federal law barred Cablevision from editing or censoring his show.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in Peeler's penalty hearing is scheduled to resume
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
