<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Brooklyn loan official convicted in contract killing scheme  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A former U.S. loan official was convicted
Wednesday of trying to arrange the killing of a witness in a New
York bank fraud trial.
</P>
<P>
   A jury found Vincent Scarabino, 60, guilty of federal
murder-for-hire charges following a 10-day trial in Brooklyn
federal court. The defendant - a former deputy director of the
Small Business Administration's Brooklyn office - was arrested in
February at his home in Spring Hills, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accused Scarabino of hatching the scheme after an
old friend, Stanley Liebman, told him he was worried that the
testimony of a former business partner would send him to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Liebman opted to cut a deal with federal authorities,
agreeing to secretly make tape recordings - played for the jury -
in which Scarabino talked about hiring two seasoned hit men to kill
the partner.
</P>
<P>
   Scarabino, who is under house arrest in Brooklyn, was ordered to
return to court on Monday, when a sentencing date is expected to be
set. He faces up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
