<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jackets' Coach Search Narrowed  </HEADLINE>
By RUSTY MILLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Columbus Blue Jackets president and
general manager Doug MacLean is narrowing the scope of his search
for a head coach, but he doesn't expect to hire anyone until after
the entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Reached on a vacation in Prince Edward Island on Wednesday,
MacLean said he has interviewed five candidates twice and still has
to interview three more people.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm still continuing the interview process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Booth News Service reported Wednesday that Detroit Red Wings
associate coach Dave Lewis had interviewed twice for the Blue
Jackets' job.
</P>
<P>
   Other publications have reported that several additional
candidates have been interviewed at least once: former Calgary
Flames head coach Dave King, Hall of Famer Bill Barber, former
Edmonton coach Ron Low, ex-San Jose assistant Paul Baxter and
current Los Angeles assistant Dave Tippett.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of those names are in the mix,'' MacLean said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has spent the past 12 years with the Red Wings, working
under head coaches Jacques Demers, Bryan Murray and Scotty Bowman.
He was an NHL defenseman for 15 years before that. The
45-year-old's focus is on the Red Wings' defense.
</P>
<P>
   When Bowman missed the start of the 1998-99 season after
offseason knee surgery, Lewis shared the head coaching
responsibilities with fellow associate coach Barry Smith,
considered to be Bowman's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL expansion draft is June 23 and the entry draft is June
24-25. The Blue Jackets, who begin play this fall, will obtain most
of their players over that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But MacLean said no coach would be in place to help with those
selections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be after the draft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, MacLean said he would prefer to hire a coach with
NHL experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''That may be an assistant coach, that may be a head coach,'' he
said. ''There's also some excellent minor pro coaches in the
American Hockey League and the IHL. We've seen the last two
expansion teams go that route.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
