<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Court Considers Sentence  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Murder or mercy?
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Supreme Court faced that question Wednesday in hearing,
for a second time, the case of a Saskatchewan farmer who killed his
severely disabled 12-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has traveled through every layer of the criminal
justice system, revolves around the appropriate punishment for
Robert Latimer: In 1993, he put Tracy Latimer in his pickup truck
and piped in exhaust fumes until she died of carbon monoxide
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy suffered from cerebral palsy that left her unable to walk,
talk or feed herself. She had undergone a series of operations on
her back, hips and legs, and Latimer has said he and his wife,
Laura, believed she faced a lifetime of painful surgery that would
amount to torture.
</P>
<P>
   Saskatchewan courts twice convicted Latimer of second-degree
murder. The first conviction, in 1994, was overturned by the
Supreme Court because some jurors had been improperly questioned by
police. The second, in 1997, carried a mandatory life sentence
without possibility of parole for 10 years, but jurors suggested a
lesser sentence to Judge Ted Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Noble agreed, calling the minimum 10-year prison term cruel and
unusual punishment under the circumstances. He invoked a rarely
used exemption from the mandatory sentence, ordering Latimer to
serve one year in prison and another year restricted to his farm.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saskatchewan appeals court overruled Noble in 1998 and
reimposed the mandatory sentence. Now the nine-member Supreme Court
must decide, in a ruling expected next year, whether Latimer
qualifies for the constitutional exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is simply a most tragic case of a man who loved his child
too much,'' Latimer's lawyer, Edward Greenspan, told the justices
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the years of legal wrangling, the case has provoked
debate among Canadians, pitting activists for the disabled and
right-to-life advocates against people who supported Latimer with
thousands of cards and letters.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Supreme Court building in Ottawa on Wednesday,
several Latimer supporters walked in slow circles, some carrying
signs. One of them, Deltry Zollmann, said Latimer only did what
''any father would do if he loved his children.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the Saskatchewan government and advocacy groups
for the disabled, who intervened in the case, said giving Latimer a
lesser sentence would effectively mean society's most vulnerable
members are unequal. They noted no appeal would exist if Tracy had
been healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There cannot be two laws -- a law for the able-bodied and a law
for people with disabilities,'' said Pat Danforth of the Council of
Canadians with Disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, however, argued that Tracy's unique circumstances
would prevent any precedent for other disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not a case of open season on the most vulnerable in
society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Sumner, a philosophy professor at the University of
Toronto, said the case has spawned suggestions that homicide laws
be expanded to offer less-severe penalties for so-called
''compassionate killings.'' No laws have changed, though.
</P>
<P>
   Sumner said Canadians generally believe Latimer committed a
crime that deserves punishment, but not the harsh sentence
mandatory for second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not merely a matter of Tracy Latimer being
disabled,'' Sumner said, noting the girl faced ''continuous pain''
and additional surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Latimer, who is free pending the Supreme Court ruling, has said
he would prefer a lengthy prison term to the alternative of seeing
Tracy suffer indefinitely. He was absent from Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess really you just hope for the best and avoid the whole
mess,'' he said of the hearing from his farm near Wilkie, in
central Saskatchewan. ''They'll get around to me soon enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
