<HEADLINE> Pat Buchanan gains New Jersey support, vows to build Reform Party  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH BRANCH, N.J. (AP) - Presidential contender Pat Buchanan
pounded home his populist points, opposing everything from world
trade agreements to illegal immigrants, and then collected New
Jersey's Reform Party delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan came to the state convention Wednesday, the same day
Reform Party leaders announced the resignation of their chairman,
who heads the effort to draft national founder Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan claimed that by the November election he will be on the
ballot in all 50 states. His campaign has been collecting delegates
and support from nearly every state Reform Party organization, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've made a long-term commitment to the Reform Party. This is
just not about running this fall. This is a long-term enterprise,''
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   That is despite attacks launched by supporters of Perot, whom
they hope will oppose him for the party nomination, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a measure of astonishment and resentment at
how very strong our efforts are,'' Buchanan told reporters.
''People feel they are being outnumbered and overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The former talk show host said his campaign is not designed to
turn the Reform Party toward his stance on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in 100 percent agreement with the Reform Party
platform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also said repeatedly he is committed to building the
Reform Party into a national organization that can eventually win
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am in this thing to win the presidency of the United States
of America and we are in this thing to build a new party that is
right,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief voting session, party members chose a slate of
delegates for the national convention in Long Branch, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The 125 party members assembled in a conference room at Raritan
Valley Community College heard delegates one by one say they
support Buchanan as their presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   They also chose a new state party chairman, Buchanan's state
campaign chairman Joe Sansone.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, Buchanan spent 40 minutes saying he was the
candidate a majority of Americans would choose as president.
Provided they could hear his message, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate said it was a cabal of national media groups
conspiring with prominent Democrats and Republicans to keep him out
of any televised debates of presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we get in those debates, we've got a fighting chance to win
it all,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also addressed Perot supporters and his own opponents,
saying he welcomed any legitimate challenge for the presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's OK, as long as they've got themselves a candidate and
they don't engage in obstruction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Buchanan told reporters that the opposition comes only
from the Perot supporters left in the party.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Buchanan was the only presidential candidate to
appear before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a full slate of Buchanan supporters,'' party official
Beverly Kidder said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gopatgo2000.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 1921 </TRAILER>
