<DOCNO> APW20000614.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family attractions planned for Camden waterfront  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - The signs posted at entrances to the city
say, ''Welcome to Camden. Experience the Rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many poor cities, there traditionally hasn't been much for
children and families to do in Camden. But that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   Ground for a minor league baseball park will be broken Thursday.
Tall ships from around the world will sail down the Delaware River
next week and opening ceremonies for the Republican National
Convention will be held on Camden's waterfront in July.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the waterfront will be home to the battleship USS
New Jersey museum, and an aerial tram will link the Camden and
Philadelphia riverfronts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a playground for adults and children,'' Paul
Drayton, executive director of the Delaware River Port Authority,
said Wednesday. The Port Authority and the Cooper's Ferry
Development Association have been the driving forces behind the new
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   -Ground will be broken Thursday for the 6,425-seat baseball
stadium. The team will be part of minor league's Atlantic League,
which includes the Atlantic City Surf and the Newark Bears. The
ballpark is expected to be completed in May and the team will begin
play in the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   -More than 20 tall ships will berth along the Delaware River for
OpSail 2000 from Friday, June 23 through Thursday, June 29. Events
will include a parade of ships, arts festival, laser shows,
fireworks and public tours of the ships.
</P>
<P>
   -Opening ceremonies for the Republican National Convention,
which begins July 31, will be held on Camden's riverfront, and
delegate and corporate events will be held at the Thomas Kean New
Jersey State Aquarium and the Sony E-Center.
</P>
<P>
   -Construction is expected to begin in the fall on an aerial tram
linking Camden and Philadelphia. The tram will be able to carry up
to 2,500 people per hour in 8-person gondolas. It will travel 165
feet in the air, next to the Ben Franklin Bridge. The tram will
land at Penn's Landing in Philadelphia and near the aquarium in
Camden.
</P>
<P>
   -The USS New Jersey Memorial will include a 250-foot pier with
an enclosed walkway and an interpretive center. The ship, which was
launched in 1942, will be restored and converted into a museum.
</P>
<P>
   -A visitors center has opened on the waterfront across the
street from the aquarium and the Camden Children's Garden. Two more
visitors centers are planned: One is scheduled to open in 2002 at
the aerial tram station and one in 2003 at Camden's light rail
station for the line being built to link Camden and Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia and Camden waterfronts attract 3 million
visitors per year. Officials hope to increase that to more than 8
million, Drayton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's going to be a model - two cities, one waterfront.
All together, it far surpasses any other waterfront,'' he said.
''It's going to be a destination in and of itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
