<HEADLINE> Man accused of killing two taken to psychiatric center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A security guard accused of killing his wife
and mother-in-law before holding his son hostage was taken
Wednesday to a state psychiatric facility.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Kemoum was transferred to the Ann Klein Forensic Center near
Trenton at the recommendation of doctors at University Hospital,
where he had stayed Tuesday after his arrest, Essex County
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemoum, 49, held his 9-year-old son hostage at their Newark home
for six hours after slashing the throats of his wife and
mother-in-law, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff ended Tuesday afternoon after a police sergeant
posed as a television cameraman and got Kemoum to release the boy,
also named Ali, in exchange for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In the ''interview,'' Kemoum, 49, accused his wife of sexual
abuse and his employers of mental abuse, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemoum walked outside and was arrested an hour later after
police told him his son was asking for him at the hospital,
although police did not know that to be the case, according to
police Director Joseph Santiago said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemoum worked as a night security guard at a Bear Stearns
brokerage in Whippany, but was unhappy that he had been unable to
find work as a chemist for five years, Mayor Sharpe James has said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemoum had lived with his son, wife Amada Dominguez and
mother-in-law Carmen Dominguez in the home for about nine years,
neighbors said. Dominguez, 54, operated a dental practice there.
</P>
