<HEADLINE> Long Branch eighth-grader dies during pool outing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Fifteen counselors were on hand Wednesday
to help Long Branch eighth-graders deal with the death of a
classmate at a pool outing.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Robertson, 14, died at 4:27 p.m. Tuesday at Raritan Bay
Medical Center, Old Bridge Division, about two hours after he was
found on the bottom of a pool at the Birch Hill Swim Club on Route
9 in Old Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Robertson's death was not immediately known. An
autopsy was expected to be performed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Bridge Police Department did not return repeated phone
calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The mood at the Long Branch Middle School was somber and some
students left early, school district spokeswoman Theresa Falcone
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kids were very upset and sad,'' she said. ''They
immediately thought of ways to honor him.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and 190 of his classmates along with 14 teachers were
at the swim club to celebrate the end of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone said there were four lifeguards - two at each shallow
and deep section - monitoring the students.
</P>
<P>
   However, a statement released by Superintendent Joseph M.
Ferraina and middle school principal Robert A. Celli indicated that
there were two lifeguards on the scene, The Asbury Park Press of
Neptune reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some students suggested that lifeguards did not respond promptly
to cries for help, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've spoken to teachers,'' Falcone said. ''Everyone responded
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcone said teachers observed Robertson swimming without any
problems in the deep section Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's class was scheduled to hold an eighth-grade dance
Wednesday night in honor of the boy, Falcone said.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors will be available through Friday and any additional
days as they are needed, Falcone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
