<HEADLINE> Attorney General's employee charged in on-line sex sting  </HEADLINE>
The Associated Press:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A scientist in the state attorney general's
office was arrested and charged with driving to New Jersey under
the mistaken belief he would have sex with a 13-year-old girl, the
FBI announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, Brian C. Johnson, 26, of Rexford, had been
communicating via the Internet with a person he thought was a
13-year-old girl, federal agents said. The ''girl'' was actually an
FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying himself by the screen name ''Bailey26,'' he made
plans to meet the girl Tuesday in Middlesex County, New Jersey to
have sex, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson arrived, though, he was greeted by members of the
North East Regional Child Exploitation Task Force who arrested him
and charged him with the federal crime of interstate travel for the
purpose of engaging a minor in a sex act.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been suspended without pay while the FBI
investigation continues, said Paul Larabee, a spokesman for
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is an environmental scientist specializing in computer
analysis of environmental issues. He was hired in February 1997 and
makes $53,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office stressed he is not a member of its
legal staff.
</P>
<P>
   Larabee would not say if Johnson used state computers in the
alleged offense. Simultaneous with his arrest, federal authorities
seized his work computer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was arraigned in U.S. District Court in Newark, N.J. and
released after posting $50,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
