<HEADLINE> Women Participation Peaks in Sydney  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- More women will compete at the Sydney
Games than at any other Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney organizers said about 3,952 women will take part, 38
percent of the total number of athletes. At the 1996 Atlanta Games,
34 percent of the athletes were women.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has supported the increased representation of women in
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Olympic Committee successfully lobbied for sexual
equality in two sports.
</P>
<P>
   The AOC said Wednesday that planned reductions in the size of
women's indoor volleyball and water polo squads had been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 women's squads for indoor volleyball had been cut from 13
to 11 players to accommodate extra beach volleyballers and the late
inclusion of women's water polo. The full quota was restored this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Women's water polo squads had initially been limited to 11
players but would now contain 13, in line with the men's water polo
squads.
</P>
<P>
   The change means an additional 24 female competitors will be
eligible for the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
