<HEADLINE> Conservatives launch ad barrage against party-swapping congressman  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Long Island voters stopping in at their local
7-Eleven will get an eyeful of a party-swapping congressman Michael
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative group that does not have to disclose their donors
has set up 50 electronic billboards on Tuesday at convenience
stores in Forbes' Suffolk County district that show the newly
minted Democrat with former House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Majority Issues Committee is also sending out
20,000 fliers to Democratic houses on eastern Long Island touting
Forbes votes for impeachment, and school prayer and against
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes became a Democrat last summer, accusing GOP House leaders
of being too extreme. Republicans now say Forbes is their top
target for defeat in November. The stakes are high. Democrats must
win only six seats to take back the House in November.
</P>
<P>
   The three-panel anti-Forbes billboards read: ''Who stood with
Newt Gingrich 100 percent? Congressman Mike Forbes stood with Newt
Gingrich 100 percent on the Contract With America.''
</P>
<P>
   They conclude: ''Call Congressman Mike Forbes and tell him you
are proud he stood by Newt Gingrich his first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was first elected in 1994 as part of the Republican
Revolution when Gingrich took control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear that the extremist Republican leaders in the House
will do anything and say anything to keep their desperate hold on
the majority,'' Forbes said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He added the attack against him was distorted, failing to
mention that he opposed Gingrich's cuts to the environment and
child care. And he said the ad blitz by the secretive group points
to the need for legislation to make tax-exempt organizations
disclose their donors.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation has gained momentum lately as spending by the
growing ranks of ''527'' groups - so named because they are created
under Section 527 of the tax code - has proliferated in
presidential and congressional campaigns this year.
</P>
<P>
   A loophole allows the groups to tell the Internal Revenue
Service that they are political organizations, but in the FEC's
eyes they are engaged in issues, not politics. Thus, they do not
have to disclose their donors like parties and political action
committees must.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to close the loophole is expected to come up for a vote
in the House before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Gallant, chairman of the Republican group, said he planned
to target 25 competitive House races this year to get the
conservative message out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mike Forbes ran as a rock-ribbed Newt Gingrich conservative
and now he's aligned himself with Hillary Clinton,'' Gallant said.
''We're making him choose between his new liberal friends and his
past voting record.''
</P>
<P>
   He maintained his group was no more secretive than organized
labor, which typically backs Democratic candidates and does not
have to disclose its members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
