<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Issues Anti-Bacterial Alert  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Amid mounting concern about the emergence of
antibiotic-resistant germs, the American Medical Association urged
the government Wednesday to step up regulation of anti-bacterial
soaps, lotions and other household products.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution adopted by the AMA's policymaking House of
Delegates stopped short of discouraging the use of such products.
</P>
<P>
   That recommendation was amended after the Cosmetic, Toiletry and
Fragrance Association expressed concern that it would alarm the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted without debate at the annual meeting
of the nation's largest organization of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the CFTA said Wednesday that the AMA is
diverting attention from proven causes of anti-bacterial resistance
and said consumers ''should continue to use anti-bacterial personal
care/cleaning products in the home with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are concerned the anti-microbial products may be
contributing to the proliferation of drug-resistant bacteria. When
a product is overused, it hastens the evolutionary process by which
bacteria develop defenses against agents designed to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA noted the development of a range of products such as
soaps, lotions and mouthwash that are advertised as containing
anti-bacterial agents to fight infection.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA said there is no scientific data showing that such
products have any infection-fighting benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The group's action follows a warning Monday from the World
Health Organization about the growth of drug-resistant infections.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the convention:
</P>
<P>
   --Rejected a resolution seeking a moratorium on gene patenting,
referring it to the AMA board of trustees for review.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to support the prescription of syringes for addicted
patients, in conjunction with addiction counseling, to help prevent
the transmission of blood-borne diseases such as AIDs.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to notify the Consumer Product Safety Commission about
the potential risk of eye injury from bungee cords. Doctors
testified about patients being blinded when the cords unexpectedly
recoiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
