<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kamin transfer criticized by Whitman critics, allies  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Critics can't seem to agree. Was Gov.
Christie Whitman too lenient or too strict in pushing Motor
Vehicles Director Richard Kamin into another high-paying state job
after a probe faulted him for bungling the new auto emissions test?
</P>
<P>
   Some Whitman critics say Kamin is being made a scapegoat, that
higher-ups and the governor herself deserve more blame for last
winter's failed unveiling of the new test.
</P>
<P>
   But others wonder how someone at the center of the $500 million
boondoggle could be retained at such a high salary.
</P>
<P>
   An investigatory panel headed by retired state Supreme Court
Justice Alan Handler last week identified six-year DMV veteran
Kamin as one of a trio of state officials who ignored or squelched
warnings that Parsons Infrastructure and Technology was unable to
deliver New Jersey's enhanced auto emissions test on time and as
promised.
</P>
<P>
   To a lesser extent, the Handler report also criticized
Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein, Environmental
Commissioner Robert Shinn and the governor's office for failing to
more closely monitor the project.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons was awarded the contract to design and construct a test
to more accurately measure tailpipe pollution to bring New Jersey
in line with federal clean air rules. But the new test has been
plagued by breakdowns and other problems since its start last
December, leading to long lines and frustrated motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman responded to the Handler report by offering Kamin a
lateral salary move from the DMV to the DOT's Office of Customer
Advocacy and Administration.
</P>
<P>
   For the same salary of $97,650, he will oversee 100 people and a
$4.8 million office budget. His new responsibilities include
department personnel, community relations, correspondences, ethics
and appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Kamin, whom the Handler report concluded was ''curiously
disengaged'' during the Parsons affair, has declined comment on the
report and his new post.
</P>
<P>
   Kamin served in the state Assembly prior to his appointment as
DMV director in 1994. At least two other former lawmakers have
worked in the same DOT office that Kamin will now head, leading
some critics to wonder whether it has become a patronage dumping
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Kamin replaces former office director Joseph Bubba, a former
state senator who landed the job after posting a key vote in favor
of Whitman's 1997 controversial pension bond sale. Former Sen. Jack
Casey, a Burlington County Democrat, was hired amid complaints in
local political circles that he sold out to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Anthony Impreveduto, D-Hudson, a frequent
Whitman critic on auto emissions, said Kamin didn't deserve to be
singled out for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Was there bungling on the whole Parsons project? Yes. Was Dick
part of it? Yes. Was he the sole person? No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that Kamin was so intimidated by pressure from the
governor's office that he failed to do what was best for the
motoring public and the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least she's showing some kind of compassion giving him
something, instead of firing him and leaving him out for the
wolves,'' Impreveduto said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Schluter, R-Mercer, one of the Legislature's
experts on ethics and government patronage, said he too was
troubled by the governor's decision to transfer Kamin.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was obviously singled out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jack Conners, D-Camden, who has criticized the
Whitman Administration's transportation policies in the past, said
Kamin deserved a demotion or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Conners found fault with Kamin's new destination, the office of
customer advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of looks like the old elephant burial ground,'' he
said. ''It's the place to put people when they don't do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough and Weinstein bristled at the
Democratic charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the governor is doing exactly the appropriate
thing,'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear there were mistakes made in the project,'' said
Weinstein. ''But to say he should be executed, I think is a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said Kamin is just the sort of person he wanted to
replace Bubba, a former lawmaker with the networking and
communication skills to ease tension in local communities over
state transportation projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 2005 </TRAILER>
