<DOCNO> APW20000614.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents urged to help enforce new law regulating pesticide use at schools </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Attorney General Richard Blumenthal and
environmental advocates on Wednesday urged parents to help enforce
a new state law regulating the use of pesticides at schools and
daycare centers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, which takes effect July 1, local or regional
school boards are required to notify parents or guardians before
pesticides are applied at schools. At the start of the school year,
school officials must provide parents and staff with a written
statement of the board's policy on pesticide use.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until this new law, parents often knew more about pesticides
applied to lawns next door than they did about pesticides applied
at schools,'' said Blumenthal. ''I think this law offers some real
opportunity for public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires schools to use licensed workers to apply
pesticides and keep records of pesticide use.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal and officials from Environment and Human Health Inc.
want parents to learn about the law and notify the state if any
school fails to comply. There is no set penalty, but Blumenthal
said the state will take violators to court seeking an order to
comply.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey by EHHI found that one-third of 77 Connecticut
school districts were routinely spraying pesticides even though
there was no known pest problem. The nonprofit organization
comprised of Connecticut doctors, public health and public policy
experts, sent surveys to 149 school districts- 77 of which
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Alderman, president of EHHI, cited Cheshire as a community
that already follows the guidelines spelled out in the law. The
town school department pays a pesticide specialist to visit the
schools every month to determine if there is a problem, rather than
spray for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five percent of the survey respondents said they only used
professional pest control operators, 12 percent said they used only
school personnel to spray, and 23 percent said they used both.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that most districts using professional pest
control operators spray more often than schools whose own personnel
do the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   EHHI also found that three school districts were still using
Dursban, which has become the center of a national debate.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the federal government and manufacturers agreed to
phase out the pesticide chlorpyrifos - commonly sold under the
trade names Dursban and Lorsban- because of the concern that it
poses health risks to children in homes, schools and parks. The
product may remain on store shelves until the end of 2001, a
decision which prompted complaints from some health advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Children are particularly sensitive to pesticides for a variety
of biological and behavioral reasons, said John Wargo, a Yale
professor who specializes in children's exposure to toxic
substances.
</P>
<P>
   EHHI was unable to track the number of children who may have
been sickened by pesticide use at schools. Symptoms of pesticide
poisoning are similar to those of flu, food poisoning or intestinal
problems, said Wargo, a member of the EHHI board. Pesticide
poisoning cannot be detected using standard blood tests.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who supported the measure said it is necessary to make
sure pesticides are applied properly and with the least exposure to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an important step,'' said Wargo.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For information on the state law and study- http://www.ehhi.org
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency-
http://www.epa.gov/ebtpages/pesticides.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
