<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Vivendi Restarts Seagram Talks
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Take Seagram Co., the Montreal-based
entertainment and liquor giant. Add France's Vivendi, the water
company. Stir gently. For $30 billion US and up, take a sip.
</P>
<P>
   The long-rumored possibility of Seagram getting swallowed up in
a large-scale corporate takeover returned Wednesday on word of
talks with Vivendi and Canal Plus, Vivendi's pay TV unit.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram and Paris-based Vivendi confirmed they're having talks
but there was no sign of a mixture that might be brought to the
table quickly and no one knew the exact size of the bar tab.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers' published estimates of the deal's value ranged from
between $30 billion US to $32.7 billion -- about $70 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram said it's in discussions ''to create a three-way
strategic business combination'' after being approached by Vivendi
and Canal Plus. ''The discussions involve an exchange of Seagram
shares for the stock of the combined entity,'' a Seagram statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Alliance MPs To Join Pension Plan
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canadian Alliance MPs who once denounced the
parliamentary pension plan as a gold-plated abomination are about
to join it -- some willingly, others grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation sponsored by the Liberal government, but
fast-tracked through the Commons with the tacit approval of
Alliance strategists, all 301 MPs will soon be members of the
contentious plan.
</P>
<P>
   That includes more than 30 Alliance members, elected as
Reformers in 1993, who until now had made a political point of
staying out.
</P>
<P>
   They would normally have to start from scratch and serve another
six years in the House before becoming eligible for retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But a special provision of the bill allows them to fork over
about $50,000 in retroactive premiums to cover the seven years they
have already spent in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   That would make them fully-paid members right away, entitled to
minimum benefits of $19,000 a year once they are out of politics
and reach age 55.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Report: Gender Barriers Exist at Top Executive Level
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Long after women break through the so-called glass
ceiling they're still picking shards of glass out of their scalps,
suggests a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Just because a woman may hold a top management position doesn't
mean that all barriers are instantly removed for the female CEO and
other women in a company, says a study by the Conference Board of
Canada, a non-profit research organization.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which is based on a survey of more than 600
executives and 94 in-depth interviews, suggests the number of women
in senior management in the private sector is half that of the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
   What's most surprising, says the report's author Barbara Orser,
are different views on how men and women believe others perceive
them as executives.
</P>
<P>
   Half the women surveyed by the board felt women managers are
perceived as being less professional and not as committed to a
corporation as their male counterparts, while three-quarters of
male CEOs disagreed with that view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
