<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York talc firm wonders about asbestos impact  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BALMAT, N.Y. (AP) - A north country producer of talc products
hopes a decision by the nation's top three crayon manufacturers to
eliminate the ingredient after it was linked to asbestos doesn't
affect other corners of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to tell because you don't know how this thing is
going to go,'' said John W. Kelse, manager of the corporate risk
management department for R.T. Vanderbilt, the Norwalk, Conn.-based
company that owns Gouverneur Talc Co.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1.3 percent of the talc produced by the company at Balmat,
Vanderbilt's largest mining and minerals processing plant, is used
in crayons. The company's fear is that other manufacturers will
eliminate talc from their products because of concerns it is
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission found small amounts of
asbestos or asbestos-like fibers when it tested crayons and
recommended crayon manufacturers come up with a substitute for the
talc. Talc is used to fortify crayons.
</P>
<P>
   Talc is also used in some chalk and modeling clay, and CPSC
Chairwoman Ann Brown said this week the agency will review the
composition of those products to see if they should also be
reformulated.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope not, but you never know,'' Kelse said.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos has been found to cause cancer and a wide variety of
lung diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Balmat is 32 miles northeast of Watertown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
