<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moynihan receives waiver to accept hefty gift  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan accepted
a $250,000 cash award from the Heinz Family Foundation, financial
disclosure forms released Wednesday show.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan received a waiver from the U.S. Senate Ethics Committee
so he could accept the gift. Senate rules limit most gifts to $50.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, the New York Democrat was awarded the Heinz
Foundation's ''Touchstone Award'' in Public Policy, the first
elected official to receive the honor.
</P>
<P>
   In making its finding that Moynihan could keep the cash, the
committee said that ''neither the Heinz Family or the Heinz Family
Foundation has a direct interest in or takes positions on
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 15, 1999, Ethics Committee letter noted that the
foundation was nonprofit and nonpartisan and has not ''targeted''
elected officials to receive the award.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Moynihan was signed by Sens. Bob Smith, R-N.H.,
and Harry Reid, D-Nev., chairman and vice-chairman of the Ethics
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Touchstone awards were established in 1992 in the memory of
Pennsylvania Sen. John Heinz, a Republican. His widow, Teresa, is
now married to Democratic Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan is the ranking Democrat on the Senate Finance Committee
and is completing his fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   His office did not immediately return a phone call seeking
comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the committee, Heinz Foundation officials said
Moynihan had been selected ''because he is the epitome of the
scholar statesman, an exemplar of the renaissance man who ... has
played a decisive role in determining how this country has and will
react to so many of the vexing social issues that have confronted
it over the last half century.''
</P>
<P>
   Past recipients of the public policy award include former
Surgeon General C. Everett Koop.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his $136,700 Senate salary, Moynihan also took in
$1,019 in royalties from some of the 18 books he has authored.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer reported a salary of $140,686 - $129,143
from the Senate and $11,543 from his final days in the House in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Among his unearned income, Schumer listed a thrift savings plan
valued at between $50,001 and $100,000 that brought him between
$2,501 and $5,000 in interest. Schumer also has a New York City
deferred compensation trust valued at between $100,001 and
$250,000. He earned between $5,001 and $10,000 on that trust.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer reported one liability - a mortgage on his home in
Brooklyn of between $50,001 and $100,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 2035 </TRAILER>
