<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Gets Sentence Shortened  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A court this week slashed from 30 years
to five the sentence of a Colombian man who admitted fatally
shooting a U.S. drug agent in a Bogota discotheque.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Figueroa, 25, already has served 19 months for the
November 1998 killings of the Drug Enforcement Agency worker and
another man. Counting good behavior and days worked in prison,
Figueroa could walk free in less than one year, his lawyer, Jaime
Rodriguez, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Overturning a lower court, the Superior Court of Bogota ruled
that Figueroa was acting in legitimate self-defense when he pulled
out a 9 mm pistol and shot Frank Moreno, a 37-year-old DEA agent,
after a scuffle. But Figueroa used excessive force in defending
himself, the court found.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the DEA, which had hailed
the original 30-year sentence handed down in January as a sign that
justice works in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa, the son of a wealthy Bogota family that owns a chain
of leather stores, turned himself in a week after the crime and
admitted to shooting Moreno after the two fought in the nightclub.
A 20-year-old bystander who caught a stray bullet in the neck also
died in the melee. Figueroa was convicted in both killings.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, of Edinburgh, Texas, had recently married and had been
in Colombia about a year when he was killed. The DEA contends the
argument in the nightclub had nothing to do with Moreno's job
duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
