<HEADLINE> One alleged pusher found unfit, the other ordered to undergo exam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - An apparently homeless man who was indicted for
allegedly trying to push two people in front of oncoming subway
trains was reported psychologically unfit to stand trial Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two court-appointed psychiatrists reported to Justice Brenda
Soloff in Manhattan's State Supreme Court that Paul O'Dwyer, 47, is
not fit to stand trial on charges of attempted murder, reckless
endangerment and assault.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney's office has until June 28 to
notify the court whether it intends to contest the finding that
O'Dwyer is unfit.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer was arrested May 22 at the Broadway-Lafayette subway
station near Houston Street in Lower Manhattan after at least two
people told police he tried to push them onto the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Justice Herbert Adlerberg ordered a mental
examination of Julio DeJesus, 36, of the Bronx, who was arrested
June 4 after he allegedly tried to throw Elizabeth Perez, 24, onto
the tracks in the subway station at 110th Street and Central Park
West. Perez was not seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   An onlooker, Rene Nunez, 26, captured DeJesus and held him for
police after he started dragging Perez toward the platform's edge.
DeJesus was charged with attempted murder, attempted assault and
reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   Adlerberg said he wanted DeJesus' psychiatric exam results by
July 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
