<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Request for Skakel juvenile records creates fuss  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - A prosecutor's attempt to find out if the
Kennedy cousin accused in the 1975 murder of Greenwich teen-ager
Martha Moxley had a juvenile record led to a court appearance
Wednesday to clear up a potential conflict of interest question.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel was charged in January in Moxley's murder, nearly
25 years after she was found bludgeoned and stabbed to death with a
golf club on her family's Greenwich estate.
</P>
<P>
   Because Skakel, now 39, was 15 at the time of the crime, his
case is being handled in juvenile court, at least initially. Skakel
is the son of Rushton Skakel, brother of Ethel Kennedy, the widow
of U.S. Sen. Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is scheduled to begin next week to decide if there is
enough evidence to hold Skakel over for trial and whether the case
will be transferred to adult court.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors prepared for that hearing, they sought any
juvenile court records pertaining to Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Their request for information went to Joanne Goldberg, a
juvenile prosecutor in Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldberg is married to Marshall Goldberg, a law partner of
Emanuel Margolis, a Stamford attorney who represents Michael
Skakel's brother, Thomas, who was a longtime suspect in Moxley's
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Goldberg told prosecutors she could not participate in
the Michael Skakel prosecution because her husband's professional
relationship with Margolis could have created a conflict of
interest. Goldberg then passed the request to Michael Panza, an
investigator in the Stamford juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   In Court Wednesday, Michael Skakel's attorney, Michael Sherman,
told Judge Maureen Dennis he did not want to have a full hearing on
the matter and later said he had ''complete faith'' in Goldberg's
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But outside court, he said he was concerned about what he called
the prosecution's ''stampede to uncover negative information about
Michael Skakel.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm concerned about some manner of unbridled prosecutorial
efforts to convict Michael Skakel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said no juvenile records were found because Skakel was
never arrested as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has never had a juvenile record - never did,'' Sherman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile records are routinely checked by both prosecutors and
defense attorneys in all cases as part of trial preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was absolutely no impropriety here,'' said Hillary
Bargar, the juvenile prosecutor who requested the records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
