<HEADLINE> Report: Mugabe May Seize Mines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe will consider
seizing foreign-owned mines and other firms as part of his campaign
to ''Africanize'' the country's assets, the Independent newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, whose government has supported the occupation of more
than 1,400 white-owned farms by black squatters this year, made his
comments in an interview with the British newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He said foreign-owned gold, copper, asbestos and iron mines face
seizure once his government completes the redistribution of
millions of acres of the white-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   ''After land, now we must look at the mining sector,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There must be Africans as owners, not just as workers,'' added
Mugabe, who said there are ''too many Britons'' in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have trained engineers of all kinds, skilled men, civil
engineers, electrical engineers, mining engineers, mechanical
engineers, geologists, agronomists, they're working everywhere,''
he said. ''But ownership? Working for who? At the end of the day
you must be able to say the resources are ours -- our people own the
mines, our people own the industry.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe said his bid to wrest economic control from Zimbabwe's
white minority will continue after parliamentary elections slated
for June 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   He said the elections will be free and fair, despite opposition
complaints that its supporters have been intimidated and attacked.
At least 31 people, most of them opposition supporters, have died
in political violence ahead of the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will be ready and willing to accept the outcome, whichever
way it goes,'' Mugabe said. But he dismissed as an ''impossible
proposition'' suggestions that the opposition Movement for
Democratic Change could win a majority.
</P>
<P>
   If opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai wins, ''then I will know
for sure that we have been visited upon by the devil,'' Mugabe
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
