<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted robber faces life in prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - A 37-year-old New Haven man faces life
in a federal prison after being convicted of robbery under the
federal ''three strikes'' provision.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Suggs was convicted Wednesday of robbery and using a
firearm during a crime of violence for the July, 14 1999 robbery of
a New Haven gas station and mini-mart. He was charged under the
Hobbs Act, which makes it a federal offense to obstruct, delay or
affect commerce by robbery, extortion or threats of physical
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Suggs is the first person in Connecticut they
have sought to convict under the ''three strikes'' rule, which
mandates a life sentence for habitual violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Suggs has a criminal record dating back to 1983
that includes convictions for robbery and assault.
</P>
<P>
   He is to be sentenced on Sept. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
