<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Seeks $16M for Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders, battling a
determined Democratic challenge to their majority, assigned
fund-raising quotas to the rank and file Wednesday as part of a $16
million effort to capture hotly competitive races this fall.
</P>
<P>
   At a closed door caucus a few blocks from the Capitol, the head
of the Republican campaign effort, Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia,
mentioned several endangered GOP incumbents by name and warned,
''If we don't get it right this year, (they) won't be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said participation in the program, dubbed Battleground
2000, would be mandatory, and committee and subcommittee
assignments in the next Congress would be influenced by individual
lawmakers' fund-raising efforts. If Republicans lose control of the
House this fall, ''committee decisions will be based on who helped
the team, not necessarily on seniority,'' according to material
prepared for the session.
</P>
<P>
   Material distributed at the session told Republicans ''if you
are unable to fulfill your commitment, please call...... to make
arrangements for a meeting with Speaker (Dennis) Hastert.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, R-Ill., made clear his interest in the effort in other
ways, deciding to assume the chairmanship of the effort and
addressing the rank and file on its importance to the party's
success this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said aspects of the program went beyond their own
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We implore our members to donate excess funds to the
committee, absolutely,'' said Erik Smith, a spokesman for the House
Democratic campaign committee. ''But we do not make leadership
positions and committee chairmanship contingent on the donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, working to gain the six seats they need to take
control of the House, have turned in a strong fund-raising effort
and held down the number of retirements from within their ranks,
two factors working to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, according to sources who attended the meeting, told
fellow Republicans the $16 million would go toward programs ranging
from ''voter turnout activities that rival the unions,'' to
campaign commercials tailored for individual districts.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged ''fundamentals like streamlined and focused
local campaigns, instead of shoehorned, cookie-cutter, national
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both parties say the outcome of about 35 races will
determine the battle for control this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Davis mentioned four in his remarks, according to one source who
attended: Reps. James Rogan and Steve Kuykendall of California,
Rep. Ernie Fletcher of Kentucky and Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   More than four months before election day, Republican
presidential contender George W. Bush leads in the polls. But Jim
Wilkinson, a spokesman for the House GOP campaign committee, said,
''We think Bush could win and we'd still lose the House if we don't
get the fundamentals done.''
</P>
<P>
   The House now has 222 Republicans, 211 Democrats and two
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats have both leaned on individual
lawmakers to pitch in for other campaigns in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Republicans mounted an effort, known as Operation
Breakout, which wound up financing late-campaign commercials that
touched on President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky
and the impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the effort turned out to be a failure because
many Republicans blame the commercials for an unexpected loss of
seats in November.
</P>
<P>
   This time, officials said the effort will be more tailored based
on the makeup of individual districts and races.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson declined to identify the three dozen or so races where
the money will be allocated. But other officials have said in
recent months they are widely scattered around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Many now are held by lawmakers retiring this fall. But each
party has a small number of incumbents expected to face
particularly difficult challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes To Cut Engine Research  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan House voted Wednesday to slash
federal subsidies for the automakers and others who conduct
research on more efficient car engines, dealing a setback to the
Clinton administration and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   By 214-211, lawmakers voted to cut $126.5 million, or about half
the budget, from the program, the partnership for a new generation
of vehicles. A majority of Republicans and dozens of Democrats
voted to shrink a program that was started by President Clinton and
strongly supported by Gore, the likely Democratic presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration, the auto industry and Michigan
lawmakers lobbied to defend the program, they were opposed by a
coalition of fiscal conservatives and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the program said it would improve the country's
energy efficiency, strengthen its economy, help consumers and lead
to a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ironic that so many House members who complain about high
gasoline prices have cut the heart out of a program designed to
save American motorists millions of dollars in energy costs in the
future,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents called it corporate welfare for the auto companies,
and said it focused too much on finding cleaner diesel engines,
which they said would still be dirty. Opponents ranged from
consumer advocate Ralph Nader to the pro-environment Sierra Club to
the conservative Citizens Against Government Waste.
</P>
<P>
   ''The federal government should not be subsidizing profitable
industries with taxpayer dollars,'' said Rep. John Sununu, R-N.H.,
who sponsored the proposal with Rep. Robert Andrews, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the program has given $19.7 million to
DaimlerChrysler, $11 million to the Ford Motor Co., and $8.7
million to the General Motors Corp., plus millions more to more
than 100 other private contractors, Sununu said.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was included in the fiscal 2001 spending bill for
the Interior Department. The Senate has not yet written its version
of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4578.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Appropriations Committee:
http://www.House.gov/appropriations
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2134 </TRAILER>
