<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High school has two cases of measles; three more suspected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CENTRAL SQUARE, N.Y. (AP) - At least two students have measles
and school officials suspect three others may be infected.
</P>
<P>
   The Oswego County Health Department is working with Central
Square School District officials to investigate the outbreak of the
disease at Paul V. Moore High School.
</P>
<P>
   The students developed the initial symptoms in mid-May,
according to health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Measles is caused by a virus and is usually spread by nasal or
throat droplets of infected persons. The symptoms usually appear in
two stages. The first stage includes runny nose, cough and slight
fever. The fever gradually increases and after three to seven days
can rise to 103-105 degrees. A red blotchy rash appears on the face
and spreads over the rest of the person's body. The eyes may appear
reddened and be sensitive to light.
</P>
<P>
   People usually develop symptoms 7-18 days after they are exposed
to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Central Square is 16 miles southeast of Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 2135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Foreign Investment Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Direct foreign investment in Venezuela
declined 25 percent between February and March of this year, the
government reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investment fell from $81 million in February to $61 million in
March, the central statistics office reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the March figure is only slightly below the year-ago figure,
when direct foreign investment was $63.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a surge in the international price of oil, Venezuela's
main export product, the economy shrank by a devastating 7 percent
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The South American nation of 23 million people appears to be
slowly emerging from the recession, however, with economic growth
of 0.3 percent posted in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been keeping their money out of the country
largely because of political uncertainty surrounding President Hugo
Chavez's ''social revolution'' for Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office 16 months ago, Chavez has decimated the
traditional political elite that ruled the country during four
decades of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The new constitution mandated elections to ''re-legitimize''
most public offices including the presidency, but balloting
originally set for May 28 was postponed due to technical glitches.
No new date for the election has been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2136 </TRAILER>
