<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Names Top Cop's Successor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana named a new
national police chief Wednesday, a day after legendary Gen. Rosso
Jose Serrano announced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Luis Ernesto Gilibert, 57, Serrano's respected deputy, will
replace the man credited with dismantling the Cali cocaine cartel,
one of the world's most powerful mafias. Gilibert has been chief of
police in the capital, Bogota, and Colombia's second-largest city,
Medellin.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano's retirement comes at a time when Colombia could use his
reputation in Washington. Pastrana is trying to persuade the U.S.
Congress to pass a $1.7 billion anti-narcotics aid package for the
South American country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials and lawmakers consider Serrano, 58, a major force
in the war on drugs. In stepping down, he said he was tired of
attending police officers' funerals. Nearly 2,000 Colombian police
were killed during his five-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Serrano's accomplishments, Colombia has the world's
highest kidnapping rate, rampant drug trafficking and street crime
and a raging guerrilla conflict in which police stations are often
attacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
