<DOCNO> APW20000614.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bryant Returns to Lakers Lineup  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Following a bit of intrigue in the Los
Angeles Lakers' locker room, Kobe Bryant returned to action
Wednesday night in Game 4 of the NBA Finals at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant hadn't played since spraining his left ankle late in the
first quarter of Game 2 last Friday against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, a second-team All-NBA selection and first-team
all-defense pick, was in the starting lineup in Game 4, and seemed
to be moving around reasonably well in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   He missed his first shot, a 15-foot jumper two minutes into the
game, but drove the baseline and fed Glen Rice shortly thereafter,
and Rice nailed a 3-pointer. Bryant made his second shot, another
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, he started out defending Pacers point guard
Mark Jackson, and forced a turnover midway through the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 21.2 points per game in the playoffs despite his
two-point effort in Game 2, Bryant appeared in the trainers' room
to be treated about an hour and 15 minutes before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, a member of the Lakers' staff taped pages
from the pre-game notes on the windows to give Bryant and the
medical staff privacy from reporters in the adjacent locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a repeat of Game 3 on Sunday night, but in that
situation reporters were allowed to peer through the windows.
Bryant exchanged smiles with media members and, at one point,
signaled with his hand he was uncertain as to whether or not he
would play.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't, because Lakers coach Phil Jackson told him not to
when Bryant approached him some 30 minutes before tipoff wanting to
play, but admitting to feeling pain when Jackson asked him to do
some lateral slides.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then told him to take the night off since the Lakers had
a 2-0 cushion in the best-of-seven series, later to become 2-1 when
Indiana won 100-91.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was sorely missed. His replacement, Brian Shaw, shot
3-of-10 in scoring six points, and none of the other Lakers stepped
up offensively or on the backboards to support Shaquille O'Neal,
who had 33 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the locker room scene Wednesday night, Jackson
told reporters Bryant had been limited in practice a day earlier,
but seemed to be laterally sliding without problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll see how it goes during the course of the game,'' Jackson
said. ''If his conditioning is pretty good, I'll stay with him for
as long as he can go. How he plays obviously has something to do
with it. His explosiveness is not there, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he believed Bryant was at about 80 percent
efficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2150 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $adv16  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's death penalty advocates are
watching the negative publicity now swirling around capital
punishment in America. But they insist they are not worried.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois' governor has suspended executions in his state after
it was found that 13 death row inmates there were deemed to have
been unfairly or wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Two disparate figures, President Clinton and Pat Robertson, have
urged states to review their death penalty procedures for fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, a Columbia Law School professor released a study
showing that between 1973-95, two-thirds of death penalty
convictions nationally were overturned on appeal. Most often, the
quality of the representation defendants received was found by
appeals court judges to have been deficient, Professor James
Liebman said.
</P>
<P>
   The capital punishment system is ''collapsing under the weight
of its own mistakes,'' Liebman declared.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with New York's death penalty law, insist two men who
helped put that statute on the books in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, New York state has done it right,'' George Pataki
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We created a (state) Capital Defender Office,'' he added. ''We
allowed not just access to quality defense attorneys, but also to
expert witnesses and to things like DNA technology. We were very
concerned in passing our bill to make sure that it's done the right
way and ours is done the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki invested a great deal of personal capital in the death
penalty. Restoring capital punishment and cutting taxes were the
twin centerpiece issues of the Republican's successful campaign for
governor against Mario Cuomo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   More than five years later, no one has been executed under the
law Pataki restored. Five inmates are on death row. The first, and
perhaps the most important, substantive constitutional challenge to
the death penalty law will not be heard by the state's highest
court, the Court of Appeals, until summer 2001 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   It will come in a case involving the trial and conviction of
Darrel Harris in 1998 for killing three people at a Brooklyn social
club.
</P>
<P>
   Staunch death penalty supporter Dale Volker, a Republican state
senator from Erie County, said he is not surprised that capital
punishment has come increasingly under fire in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In times when murder rates and crime rates have dropped
dramatically, critics tend to assail capital punishment and other
stringent anti-crime laws as no longer necessary, Volker argued.
</P>
<P>
   He blames such a mindset in New York in the early 1960s for
compelling the state Legislature to abolish the death penalty - New
York last executed a murderer in 1963 - and to countenance light
penalties for dealers of hard drugs. The much-reviled Rockefeller
Drug laws were a harsh response at what years of laxness had
wrought, especially in inner-city neighborhoods across the state,
Volker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senator said he believes he can explain to some
extent Liebman's findings of widespread inadequacy in the defense
of death penalty cases. Judges are ''very, very reluctant'' to let
a defendant move toward execution if there is even a ''wisp'' of
impropriety with that person's defense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volker also suggested that defense lawyers themselves, knowing
their cases are hopeless, might be tempted to risk violating
ethical canons and to make errors that would ''win'' their
defendants new trials as part of a campaign to delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can get a retrial after 10 years, it is almost
impossible to get a death penalty conviction'' due to the passage
of time, the death or disappearance of witnesses, the loss of
evidence and other factors, Volker reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   ''You delay, delay, delay, then you complain about the delays in
court,'' said Volker, a one-time police officer who is a lawyer.
''They say, 'Boy this thing is costing a ton of money.' ... It's a
game, I hate to say it, it's sort of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Capital Defender Office is compiling the voluminous
brief it hopes will convince the state Court of Appeals next summer
that New York's new death penalty law is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But it will have trouble using Liebman's study as fodder. To do
so, the Capital Defender Office would have to argue that Harris did
not receive proper representation at his trial - from the Capital
Defender Office.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Capitol Defender Office has won praise for its
expertise and the job it has done defending those possibly facing
the death penalty, office spokeswoman Pauline Toole said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
