<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Crackdown Targets Securities Fraud
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Charges were brought today against 120 people in what
federal prosecutors said was the largest securities fraud crackdown in U.S.
history. Among those charged were members of all five New York City organized
crime families. The far-reaching fraud stretched over five years, and never
before have so many people been charged at once in such a case, U.S. Attorney
Mary Jo White said. She said 98 of them had been arrested by early afternoon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Southern Baptists: No Women Pastors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Southern Baptist Convention decided today that
women should no longer serve as pastors. The vote came two years after the
denomination said a wife should submit herself to the servant leadership of her
husband. ''Southern Baptists, by practice as well as conviction, believe
leadership is male,'' said the Rev. Adrian Rogers of Memphis, Tenn., chairman of
the drafting committee of a revised Faith and Message statement. ''While men and
women are gifted ... the office of pastor is limited to men by Scripture.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Leaders of Koreas Talk, Progress Made
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In a breakthrough at their historic summit, the
leaders of North and South Korea signed an agreement Wednesday aimed at easing
half a century of conflict on the Korean Peninsula and working toward eventual
reunification. The two leaders also agreed to allow reunions of families, to
hold another summit and to promote South Korean investment in the North's
failing economy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FTC To Check High Gas Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission became the latest federal
agency to agree to investigate a spike in gasoline prices in the Midwest, with
prices above $2 a gallon in Milwaukee -- 23 percent above the national average.
Investigators will explore whether any competitive behaviors, such as
price-fixing or collusion, are driving prices higher, FTC spokesman Mitch Katz
said today. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the U.S. Energy
Department sent teams of investigators to Milwaukee earlier this week to examine
the issue amid a clamor of consumer anger and calls from politicians for
government to do something to reduce prices.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Army Reserve Col. Charged With Spying
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A retired Army Reserve colonel was arrested today,
accused of spying for the Soviet Union during a 25-year Cold War conspiracy
while he worked in Germany. The U.S. Attorney's Office identified him as George
Trofimoff. Prosecutors called him the highest-ranking U.S. military officer ever
charged with espionage. They said he conspired to sell classified military
intelligence information to the Soviets when he was a civilian employee of the
Army.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Strikes La. School Prayer Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONROE, La. (AP) -- A federal judge today struck down a Louisiana law that
allows public schools to set aside time for prayer. A 1976 law initially allowed
for silent meditation. It was amended in 1992 to include the word ''prayer'' and
again last year to remove the word ''silent.'' The change to verbal prayer
amounted to an unconstitutional endorsement of religion by the Legislature,
federal Judge Robert James ruled today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Push for High-Tech Visas Stalled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Not long ago, Congress appeared to be moving to address
the high-tech industry's pleas for more workers, but now bills to allow more
skilled foreigners into the country have stalled and the industry is worried.
Increasing the number of H-1B visas, which allow college-educated foreigners to
work in the United States for up to six years, is a top priority for high-tech
companies striving to fill an estimated 300,000 vacancies nationwide. ''If we
don't solve this problem, all we're doing is make our companies less
competitive,'' said Roger Coker, head of U.S. recruiting for Texas Instruments.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 66; Nasdaq Drops 54
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved in divergent directions today, with blue-chip
issues rising after a closely watched inflation gauge rose less than expected.
Technology stocks slumped, led by industry leaders like Qualcomm and Intel. The
Dow Jones industrial average was up 66.11 at 10,687.95. On the NYSE, advancing
issues outpaced decliners, 1,690-1,253. The Nasdaq composite index fell 53.65 at
3,797.41.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hamilton Signs Deal With Wizards
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Jordan wanted a college coach for his Washington
Wizards, a team short on discipline and fundamentals, and he got it: Leonard
Hamilton of the University of Miami. Hamilton signed a five-year, $10 million
contract with the Wizards today and accepted with relish his new lofty
assignment. Hamilton is the Wizards' fifth coach in three seasons. The team
hasn't won a playoff game in 12 years, with the only postseason appearance since
1988 coming in a three-game, first-round sweep by Chicago in 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
