<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC To Check High Gas Prices  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT IMRIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politicians in Illinois and Wisconsin are seeking suspension of
federal fuel regulations blamed for rocketing gasoline prices above
$2 a gallon in Chicago and Milwaukee in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Federal Trade Commission became the latest
federal agency to agree to investigate whether any competitive
behaviors, such as price-fixing or collusion, are driving prices
higher, FTC spokesman Mitch Katz said Wednesday from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the U.S. Energy
Department sent teams of investigators to Milwaukee earlier this
week to examine the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Gov. George Ryan said the high pump prices in the
Chicago area coincided with the June 1 deadline the Environmental
Protection Agency set for oil companies to begin producing
cleaner-burning reformulated fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current craziness doesn't make any sense,'' Ryan said at a
Wednesday news conference. ''Something just isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, prices have risen nationwide, but have soared
in the Midwest, particularly in Chicago and Milwaukee. The average
cost of regular gas on Wednesday was $2.11 a gallon in Chicago, $2
in Milwaukee and $1.61 nationwide, according to the American
Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he agrees with the goal of the federal program
to clean air pollution, but the EPA implemented the new rules too
quickly and without regard for consumer impact.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he has written five letters -- without response --
requesting an EPA rollback its rules, although not all the way back
to the dirtier fuels of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson and nine members of Wisconsin's
congressional delegation, including Kohl, have asked the EPA to
temporarily waive the requirement that only cleaner-burning
gasoline be sold in six southeast Wisconsin counties, including
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokesman Dave Ryan said Wednesday the agency was reviewing
that request.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices have risen steadily since May when service stations
started selling a new type of reformulated gas designed to cut down
on air pollution in the nation's biggest cities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to supply problems with the new formulations, Erin
Roth of the Wisconsin Petroleum Council, said other factors
contributing to the runup in gas prices include the high cost of
crude oil, increased demand during summer driving season and a
patent dispute over the process to make reformulated gas.
</P>
<P>
   Service stations just outside the six-county region in
southeastern Wisconsin where reformulated gas is required are
running out of fuel as motorists line up to save 20 cents or more
per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inside the boundary, service station owners told the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel that business has gone down as much as
50 percent and may force layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Mario Fox in Chicago contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
