<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Won't Withdraw From Congo  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda on Wednesday blasted U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan for recommending sanctions if the
central African nation does not withdraw its troops from Congo,
saying such a resolution would end Congo's fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not going to leave ... until our security is
guaranteed, and we make no apologies about this,'' said Seth
Kamanzi, a senior Rwandan Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Annan urged the U.N. Security Council to demand that
both Rwanda and Uganda immediately withdraw from the northern
Congolese city of Kisangani, where they clashed last week, and that
they then make a complete pullout from Congo. Under Annan's
proposal, sanctions could be imposed if the two armies refuse to
leave the parts of Africa's third-largest nation they control in
cooperation with rebels who are trying to topple Congolese
President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan officials told reporters that while Rwanda is committed
to completing its withdrawal from Kisangani, which is supposed to
be handed over to unarmed U.N. military observers, it will not
leave Congo until other foreign troops have done so, in accordance
with the peace accord signed last year in Lusaka, Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Security Council goes on with this, Lusaka will be
dead,'' Ambassador Mike Rwigema said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, meanwhile, there were already signs that the
sanctions threat might end up being removed.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council opened initial consultations Wednesday on a
French draft resolution based on Annan's proposal. The council has
said it wants to adopt the resolution Friday. Such a tight deadline
and early indications of disagreement on other elements of the
draft indicated that the warning of sanctions -- the draft's most
divisive element -- could be watered down or removed altogether by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda, and later Uganda, sent troops and arms into Congo to
back up the anti-Kabila rebels in August 1998. But since then, the
two allies have fallen out over the conduct of war and which rebels
to support, culminating in repeated clashes for the control of
Kisangani, the Congo River port that both sides deem strategic for
resupplying their troops elsewhere in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The two armies fought pitched artillery battles for seven days
last week in Kisangani, killing at least 150 civilians and injuring
more than 1,100. The fighting ended Sunday after the Rwandan army
drove the Ugandans out of the northern sector of Kisangani and let
unarmed U.N. military observers deploy between the two former
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Both armies were in the process of withdrawing from the city
when fighting broke out, and they have now agreed to complete the
withdrawal, said Senegalese Gen. Muntaga Diallo, head of the U.N.
observer mission in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the fighting has further complicated the already
fragile peace accord between Congolese President Laurent Kabila,
the rebels and the five foreign armies involved in the war -- Rwanda
and Uganda on the rebel side and Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia on
Kabila's side.
</P>
<P>
   Their withdrawal from Congo is supposed to be supervised by a
5,537-strong force of U.N. observers and troops. So far, just 200
observers have been deployed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
