<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of historical home wants to build golf course there  </HEADLINE>
prhfc
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, Conn. (AP) - The owner of a home that served as
headquarters to French troops during the American Revolution wants
to put a golf course on the property.
</P>
<P>
   William W. Landon said he plans to name the nine holes on the
chip-and-putt course after Lebanon's many historical heroes, some
of whom lived in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Redwood, the home Landon said he saved from demolition and has
been restoring for 15 years, will remain unaltered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing will be spared to make it the best, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Historians are aghast at the golf course plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're talking about a house that is not only historic, but is
directly across the street from the Congregational church, the town
hall, the green itself, the library - you name it, '' said local
historian Alicia Wayland. She also lives on the green.
</P>
<P>
   David Trumbull, the son of Gov. Jonathan Trumbull and father of
Gov. Joseph Trumbull, built Redwood in 1778 for his new bride,
Sarah Backus of Norwich.
</P>
<P>
   In 1780, they turned the home over to the French army unit
considered to be the most colorful and troublesome of the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   Landon's house, and the entire area surrounding the green, is
listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The designation is less of a deterrent to altering private
property than to projects proposed by the government, said Jack
Shannahan, director of the Connecticut Historical Commission. In
this case, the historical home is not being destroyed so the
designation carries little weight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shannahan has sent the town a letter urging officials to
consider the historical heritage of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Landon said the project will blend well with the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It fits wonderfully,'' he said. ''It would be an asset to the
town. I look to the right, I see the Lebanon green store. I look
across the street, I see the Lebanon Town Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   The town zoning commission, which held a public hearing on the
proposal Wednesday night, did not indicate when they would rule on
Landon's request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 2214 </TRAILER>
