<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Assault Rebel Camp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COTABATO, Philippines (AP) -- Air force planes dropped bombs and
helicopters fired rockets Wednesday at a major Muslim rebel camp in
the southern Philippines, the military said, forcing 40,000
villagers to flee their homes to escape the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Two army battalions took part in the assault on the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front outpost near the boundary of Maguindanao and North
Cotabato provinces, said army spokesman Capt. Noel Detoyato. The
thousands of people from surrounding villages who fled their homes
pitched makeshift shelters in nearby town centers, local social
work officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Rajamuda is one of two remaining major MILF camps in the
southern Mindanao region. The army attack on the camp came several
hours after guerrillas ambushed a convoy bearing a Philippine
general, Detoyato said. Maj. Gen. Gregorio Camiling was unhurt in
the ambush in Maguindanao province, but one soldier was wounded and
one armored vehicle was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The MILF is the larger of two groups fighting for an independent
Islamic state in the southern Philippines. The smaller but more
radical group, the Abu Sayyaf, is holding 21 mostly foreign
hostages on southern Jolo island.
</P>
<P>
   Military operations against the rebels intensified in late April
after the government decided to shut down dozens of MILF satellite
camps. At least 184 government soldiers and militiamen have been
killed and more than 680 wounded in clashes since January -- the
most serious fighting in Mindanao since the height of the Muslim
rebellion in the 1970s. There are no reliable figures on rebel
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Government and rebel negotiators resumed peace talks two weeks
ago, but the military operations have continued. Another round of
talks is scheduled for June 28.
</P>
<P>
   In Manila, President Joseph Estrada met with religious and
business leaders who are calling for a cease-fire in Mindanao.
Estrada said he joined them in their call for peace, but defended
the military operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are one in our quest not just for temporary peace, but more
importantly, lasting peace,'' he said, citing 227 alleged rebel
violations of a 1997 cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   When the violations became ''too much,'' Estrada said, ''I
reluctantly ordered the armed forces to meet what has now become a
full-scale military challenge to government authority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2227 </TRAILER>
