<HEADLINE> Pacers Lead Lakers 54-51 at Half  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rik Smits was almost an even match for
Shaquille O'Neal as the Indiana Pacers, looking for a victory to
tie the NBA Finals, led the Los Angeles Lakers 54-51 at halftime of
Game 4 on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Smits was dominated by O'Neal in the series' first three games,
but the veteran center made his first five shots and delighted the
Conseco Fieldhouse crowd as the Pacers, down 2-1 in the series,
tried to give Los Angeles consecutive losses for just the fourth
time all season.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led 33-23 after the first quarter, but the Lakers closed
the gap steadily in the second. Robert Horry's three-point play
with 1:59 left in the half cut the Pacers' lead to 50-49 before
Austin Croshere and Reggie Miller, who led Indiana with 13 points,
both scored late.
</P>
<P>
   But the most surprising aspect of the half was the performance
of Smits, who fed off the crowd's emotion and stood up to the
league MVP. Though O'Neal finished the half strong and got 13
points by hitting his last four shots, Smits had 10 points on
5-of-7 shooting, giving the Pacers an undeniable morale boost.
</P>
<P>
   Smits hit his first five shots until O'Neal, who had eight
rebounds in the half, blocked a fallaway jumper with 5:32 left in
the half. But the Pacers went right back to Smits, and he drew
O'Neal's third personal foul on the next possession.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles got a boost of its own with the return of Kobe
Bryant, who sprained his left ankle early in Game 2 and missed all
of Game 3 but was in the Lakers' starting lineup. He played the
entire first quarter and much of the second, going 3-of-7 from the
field for six points and getting four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant moved without obvious limitations but seemed unsure of
the strength in his foot as he missed his first shot and was called
for a traveling violation early. One of the NBA's premiere
defenders, Bryant was assigned to guard light-scoring Mark Jackson
in an apparent concession to his injury.
</P>
<P>
   With the Indiana crowd screaming even louder than in Game 3, the
Pacers came out red-hot. They hit eight of their first 10 shots,
including two 3-pointers by Miller, to take a seven-point lead in
the opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Miller finished the first quarter with 10 points despite going
just 2-of-6 from the field, but he then went scoreless until the
final minute of the half, missing his only shot. The Pacers'
offensive star had a similar lapse in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed four of his first five shots from the field before
finding his legs. Against Smits, Dale Davis and Sam Perkins, he
looked frustrated and made an unusual appeal to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, who criticized Lakers coach Phil Jackson for his lack
of playing time in the series, played a much bigger role in Game 4.
He scored eight points on 2-of-4 shooting but took the ball to the
hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Horry had 10 points off the bench for Los Angeles, while Rick
Fox had five. Croshere led the Pacers' bench with eight points,
while leading scorer Jalen Rose had six quiet points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, playing on his 39th birthday, hit a 3-pointer in the
first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
