<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal in Albany to require sale of 'fire-safe' cigarettes  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Legislature and Gov. George Pataki
reached a deal Wednesday to require the sale of self-extinguishing
cigarettes in New York state by mid-2003.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved unanimously by the state Assembly and
Senate late Wednesday night, is designed to cut down on instances
where smokers cause fires through careless smoking or when they
fall asleep and start upholstery or mattresses smoldering.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials estimate that at least a third of the fire deaths
in the state occurred in blazes sparked by careless smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is a reworked version of a bill Pataki vetoed on
May 25. That decision angered anti-smoking forces, who are riding
high in Albany this year after seeing the state's per-pack
cigarette tax go up from 56 cents to $1.11 starting March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill gives the state more time to set up guidelines for
the self-extinguishing characteristics of cigarettes and,
consequently, for tobacco companies to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   The first measure required the marketing of only ''fire-safe''
cigarettes starting in April 2002. The new bill would give the
state two years to come up with the cigarette standards starting on
Jan. 1, 2001, and then tobacco companies would get until July 1,
2003, to begin marketing cigarettes meeting the guidelines
exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   The safety standards would be developed jointly by the state
Office of Fire Prevention and the state Health Department under the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also mandate that fire-safe cigarettes
cannot be more toxic to smokers than the conventional cigarettes
currently on the market. One of the objections in Pataki's veto
message was that no such stipulation was in the original bill.
</P>
<P>
   Included with the fire-safe cigarette bill was a related measure
to increase penalties and otherwise beef up state efforts to combat
''buttlegging'' - the sale of untaxed cigarettes. Critics say
bootlegging is already a serious problem, and would only get worse
when conventional cigarettes are taken off the market in favor of
the self-extinguishing variety.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Sciandra of the Center for a Tobacco Free New York said
his group is ''incredibly happy'' about the new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sciandra and the bill's chief sponsor in the Assembly,
Democrat Alexander Grannis of Manhattan, said they think a New York
statute is likely to compel the tobacco industry to seek a
nationwide law in Congress rather than ing with state statutes
piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''They panic,'' Grannis said. ''We will change this entire
industry, change how this industry manufactures its product.''
</P>
<P>
   A chief Senate sponsor of the bill, Queens Republican Frank
Padavan, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be voting today for self-extinguishing cigarettes to
save the lives of New Yorkers, but we are also igniting a bonfire
in the halls of Congress,'' Padavan said. ''The campaign started
here, but the best possible remedy would be a national fire-safe
cigarette standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, a bill requiring fire-safe cigarettes in
California appeared before a state legislative committee in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kottak, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson, said that
trying to make a cigarette which would ''pass an artificial test
could have a direct, adverse impact'' on the health of smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris spokeswoman Kati Otto said her company has been
test-marketing a cigarette that is less likely to ignite certain
fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results both in the laboratory and in the test market have
been extremely positive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris thinks a national approach to mandating
self-extinguishing cigarettes ''is preferable to 50 potentially
conflicting state standards,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
