<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Down Broadway on a lawn mower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Broadway is known for lots of things - bright
lights, theater, yellow cabs - but lush lawns aren't among them.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop Gary Hatter, who drove his lawn mower down
Broadway on Wednesday as part of what he says will be a five-month
effort to break the world record for longest distance traveled on a
mower.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never come through anyplace like that,'' said Hatter, 46,
of Champaign, Ill., who was on his first visit to New York.
''Weaving in and out of cabs, them weaving in and out of you. ...
The traffic, the people. It's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatter, who began his trip in Portland, Maine, two weeks ago,
woke up Wednesday morning in Greenwich, Conn., and made it all the
way to midtown Manhattan on his big orange Kubota lawn mower, model
BX-2200, complete with a plastic roof.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people were just unbelievable, waving and thumbs up,'' he
said. ''I didn't stop, I was rolling. A lot of them would pull up
alongside me and congratulate me, wish me the best of luck. ... It
was wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatter's first sight of New York City came when he entered the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was nothing but shops one right after another,'' he said
later. ''I'd never seen so many people before. I was like, 'Holy
mackerel!'''
</P>
<P>
   After a day or two in New York, he plans to head for Trenton,
N.J., then toward North Carolina and through several Southern
states. After that, he'll veer north and head cross-country to
Seattle, go south to Los Angeles and then return east on a southern
route. All told, he expects to cover 14,000 miles in 150 days.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter, a former truck driver who hasn't worked in 21 years
because of a back problem, plans to break the current lawn mower
driving record, 4,039 miles over 51 days. He hopes his ride will
raise enough money for a back operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-14-00 2253 </TRAILER>
