<HEADLINE> Former shuttle commander urges girls into space  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CORNING, N.Y. (AP) - The first female space shuttle commander
said she hopes more girls get involved in the space program as the
world strives to explore more of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Collins, who commanded a shuttle flight in July 1999,
urged young women to pursue the sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're out there looking for women. And why, when we send out
our applications, why are only 18 to 20 percent women? Women do not
select technical fields for their career at the same rate as men. I
try to encourage young women to do what you enjoy, don't let
someone else tell you what to do with your life,'' she said at the
Ernie Davis Heisman Memorial Dinner Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Collins sees exploration into deeper space as the next logical
step for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the more distant future, back to the moon, onto Mars, but
the bottom line is we need to continue to expand,'' she said. ''I
hope to be alive when the first person walks on Mars, and I hope
that person is an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, an Elmira native, Dikembe Mutombo, a center for the
Atlanta Hawks, and John Mackey, a former football player for
Syracuse University and the Baltimore Colts, received humanitarian
awards at the dinner named for the 1961 Heisman Trophy winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
