<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Public Workers Protest  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WARREN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Thousands of Venezuelan public workers
took to the streets of Caracas on Wednesday in a march to protest
the government's labor policy.
</P>
<P>
   The main union -- the Venezuelan Workers Federation, or CTV --
accuses the government of violating international labor laws by not
negotiating a new collective labor agreement for the public sector.
The workers are demanding a 20 percent increase in salary that
President Hugo Chavez had promised would take effect in May.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 people turned out for the march Wednesday morning,
and some 40 policemen carrying anti-riot gear set up a barricade
outside the gates of the presidential palace. Marchers were urging
the government to restart negotiations for a new collective
agreement, acting union head Cesar Cedeno told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Ortega, who works for a government arts foundation, joined
several other workers in carrying a cardboard corpse -- an effigy of
Chavez -- in a mock funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're carrying this corpse to protest the insecurity and
unemployment in the country, and the disrespect Chavez has shown to
us workers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before it was dissolved on Jan. 31, a powerful assembly
that rewrote Venezuela's constitution suspended labor negotiations
with the public sector for six months. It also mandated the
election of a new union leadership. Chavez, a former coup leader
who took office 16 months ago promising a ''social revolution'' for
Venezuela, has repeatedly said current union leaders are part of a
corrupt oligarchy that needs to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio program earlier Wednesday, Finance Minister Jose
Rojas said the union doesn't have a legitimate reason to protest
because the government is abiding by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Although Venezuela is the third-largest oil exporter in the
world, more than half the country lives in poverty. In March, the
official unemployment rate reached a record high 16 percent, though
private economists put the rate at closer to 25 percent. More than
half the labor force works in the ''informal economy,'' selling
wares in flea markets and on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.3 million Venezuelans work for the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000614.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican City Evacuated for Flood  </HEADLINE>
By LUIS LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- Authorities evacuated more than 200
people from their homes in this southern Mexican city Wednesday
after officials opened the floodgates of a dangerously full dam for
the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers surrounding Villahermosa, population 475,000, were
already swelling to alarming levels late Wednesday. Officials said
the rivers could rise as much as 20 inches over the next few days
as the water is slowly let out of the Penitas dam, which swelled
beyond its capacity after recent heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh my God, we're going under again,'' resident Demilde Sosa
said upon hearing the alert over the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say water has to be released from the dam to prevent
it from breaking and creating an even greater disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 230,000 residents of the city were
evacuated during a month of flooding that caused some of the worst
damage in the country. Waters rose to the rooftops of
already-flooded homes and businesses after officials opened the
dam, causing 60,000 people who had stayed behind to flee their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the city will suffer another disaster like last
year's thanks to prevention efforts such as walls of sandbags that
are already in place, said the director of the local Civil
Protection agency, Sergio Jimenez. Nonetheless, he warned that
residents of low-lying areas should be prepared to leave.
</P>
<P>
   So far, half a dozen neighborhoods and outlying communities are
flooded. Families started leaving their homes late Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2310 </TRAILER>
