<HEADLINE> Lakers Lead Pacers 80-77 After 3  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Kobe Bryant heated up and Shaquille O'Neal
kept pounding away as the Los Angeles Lakers took a 80-77 lead over
the Indiana Pacers after three quarters of Game 4 on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who needed a victory to tie the NBA Finals, led the
entire first half but fell behind as Bryant, who sprained his left
ankle early in Game 2 and missed Game 3, scored 10 of his 16 points
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who dueled surprising Indiana center Rik Smits to a draw
in the first half, racked up 20 points and 17 rebounds after three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana suffered from the disappearance of Reggie Miller, who
scored 10 points in the first quarter but had just one field goal
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant picked up his fourth personal foul just seconds into the
third quarter, but he then scored on three straight possessions to
pull Los Angeles within 58-57. The Lakers took their first lead of
the game at 62-60 on Glen Rice's 3-pointer with 8:00 left in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's dunk with 2:30 left in the quarter gave Los Angeles a
73-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led 33-23 after the first quarter, but the Lakers closed
the gap steadily in the second and trailed 54-51 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana got an unexpected contribution from Smits, who hit his
first five shots of the game and had 16 points through three
quarters. Smits made three short hook shots in the third quarter
and even drew a technical foul against Ron Harper, who smacked
Smits on the shoulder as he ran through a pick.
</P>
<P>
   Smits was dominated by O'Neal in the series' first three games,
but the veteran center delighted the Conseco Fieldhouse crowd as
the Pacers, down 2-1 in the best-of-seven series, tried to give Los
Angeles consecutive losses for just the fourth time all season.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant moved without obvious limitations but started slowly,
seemingly unsure of the strength in his foot. One of the NBA's
premiere defenders, Bryant was assigned to guard light-scoring Mark
Jackson in an apparent concession to his injury.
</P>
<P>
   With the Indiana crowd screaming even louder than in Game 3, the
Pacers came out red-hot. They hit eight of their first 10 shots,
including two 3-pointers by Miller, to take a double-digit lead in
the opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Miller finished the first quarter with 10 points but barely
touched the ball in the next two quarters. The Pacers' offensive
star had a similar lapse in Game 3, and he didn't have a
fourth-quarter field goal in the series' first three games.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed four of his first five shots from the field before
finding his legs. Against Smits, Dale Davis and Sam Perkins, he
looked frustrated and made an unusual appeal to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who criticized Lakers coach Phil Jackson for his lack of
playing time in the series, played a much bigger role in Game 4,
scoring 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry had 10 points off the bench for Los Angeles, while
Rick Fox added eight. Croshere led the Pacers' bench with 10
points, while leading scorer Jalen Rose had 10 points on 4-of-11
shooting through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, playing on his 39th birthday, hit a 3-pointer in the
first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2319 </TRAILER>
