<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Toldeo: OAS On the Line  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Former presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo
said Wednesday that the Organization of American States will lose
credibility if it offers just lukewarm criticisms of President
Alberto Fujimori's government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our expectation is that the OAS won't merely salute to the
flag,'' said Toledo, who boycotted the May 28 presidential runoff
vote, claiming it was rigged. ''If it does, the OAS's credibility
in the region will be very seriously examined.''
</P>
<P>
   An OAS delegation refused to monitor the voting, saying the
election was ''far from what could be considered free or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 34-member nations later stopped short of questioning
Fujimori's win or imposing sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they are sending OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria and
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy to Peru at the end
of the month to work on strengthening democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is still weighing its reaction to the
election. But a growing number of analysts are saying it is
extremely unlikely that Peru will face any international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he still does not recognize Fujimori's lopsided
victory, which gave him an unprecedented third five-year term.
Toledo has vowed prevent Fujimori's inauguration before Congress on
July 28 with massive street protests.
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces last week pledged allegiance to Fujimori -- a
move that Toledo maintains was unconstitutional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-14-00 2321 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
