<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-14 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special aid package for Nassau, NYC, Yonkers, Buffalo  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Legislature voted Wednesday to
bail out one of the wealthiest counties in America, plus give
fiscal boosts to New York City, Yonkers and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The aid package for Nassau County is designed to get the Long
Island county out from under a current shortfall of more than $100
million which is projected to grow to more than $300 million by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bailout deal, the county has agreed to make about $200
million in spending cuts over the next four years while state
taxpayers will contribute $105 million to the county over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-member, state-appointed board will oversee the county's
finances and if local officials fail to take a fiscally prudent
course, the panel will turn into a formal financial control board
with direct budgeting powers in the county.
</P>
<P>
   The county will also be able to save tens of millions of dollars
in interest costs by refinancing some of its current $2.7 billion
in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout bill was negotiated with the input of Gov. George
Pataki, and he is expected to sign the measure into law.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County counts some of the wealthiest residents in New
York state among the 1.3 million people within its boundaries just
east of New York City. Its median annual income of $58,155 is among
the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the county's budgeting say administrators and the
local legislature got into fiscal trouble by going eight of the
past 10 years without raising property taxes. In the meantime,
county expenses and the cost of labor contracts continued to go up.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Nassau County bailout, the Legislature also
agreed to have state taxpayers cover the interest on a 30-year loan
for $45 million to be taken out by Buffalo taxpayers; to allow New
York City to raise its debt ceiling from $7.5 billion to $11.5
billion; and to allow Yonkers to sell $10 million in bonds to share
the costs of a court-ordered desegregation plan.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Martin Connor said Wednesday the state
has begun to establish a dangerous precedent with bailouts like
those for Nassau County and, a few years ago, the city of Troy.
Whereas in the mid-1970s New York City repaid ''every cent'' of the
borrowing it had to do to pull itself back from the brink of
bankruptcy, the state has come to simply grant large sums of state
taxpayer dollars to troubled municipalities, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course it begs the question that has been on everyone's
mind for a year or more: 'What exactly is wrong in Nassau
County?''' Connor told his colleagues in the Senate. ''A lot is
wrong there. What is good is there seems to be a bipartisan effort
to get to that answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor said the state probably has no choice but to intervene in
Nassau County's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The threat, not only to the taxpayers of Nassau County but to
the whole fiscal structure of the state, is very, very real if one
of our largest counties is permitted to founder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Alexander Grannis, a Manhattan Democrat,
blamed Nassau's problems on ''profligate spending'' and
''inappropriate management'' by county administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Grannis said there is a fundamental unfairness in making Buffalo
and Yonkers repay the money they are borrowing while giving Nassau
County state money free and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stepping in is one thing, but giving money to the wealthiest
county in the state and one of the wealthiest in the country
without any requirement whatsoever that that money be repaid to the
state of New York is totally inappropriate,'' Grannis said.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County is also facing an ultimatum from Wall Street:
correct its finances by June 30 or face a devaluation of its bond
rating to junk status.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong political overtones to the issue. Republicans
have lost control to Democrats of the state Legislature in Nassau
County, apparently due to the financial morass, for the first time
since World War I. Republicans in the Senate need to return several
members from the county to their chamber this November to maintain
the GOP's majority in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
